Observation Details: One swift was viewed for approximately 90 minutes, flying over the pond among a large mixed group of swallows (including Tree, Violet-green, Bank, Rough-winged, Barn and Cliff). When the swift came close, it seemed larger/bulkier than the surrounding swallows, slower and easier to track. It was dark grey-brown overall, with bulky wings. Wings long, inner primaries always bulging. Throat lighter than chest, rump close to same shade as back. One birder thought they heard it give loud single-note chirp calls every time it approached. However, no audio was recorded and with so many birds present, one can't be certain which bird was calling. Photos included, brief video here https://youtu.be/1QY1zFmTjOQ  More photos below.

Un premier individu repéré par hasard alors qu'il vole bas au dessus du garage au bout de la Rue Girard, silencieux. Circule autour du bout de la rue puis est rejoint par un deuxième individu. Rodent ensemble et font des allers et retours le long de la Rue Principale en criant quelques fois un crepitement. Silhouette unique de cigare, ailes longues et courbées par en arrière, bec minuscule, secondaires très courtes probablement en mue. Battement d'ailes très rapides suivis de courts vols planés, parfois les ailes tenues en l'air, rappellant vaguement un engoulevent. Retrouvés plus tard sur la Rue Principale, à mi chemin entre la Rue Girard et la Rue de l'Église. Il y a là deux vieilles maisons face à face avec chacune une très vieille cheminée en briques rouges. Les martinets tournent autour de ces maisons, volent parfois très bas et frôlent les toits, crient sans arrêt, font des paradent nuptiales ensemble fréquemment, sont même parfois agressifs avec moi en me volant juste au dessus de la tête. Un individu vu plus tard transporter une petite branche !

Observation Details: I sat in the shade trying to photograph Chimney Swifts entering their brick chimney nest at 506 Erie Street. They flew so fast, it was almost impossible to react fast enough to trigger the shutter while they were in frame. My camera was on a tripod in the yard, triggered from across the yard with a remote. I had the camera’s shutter speed set at 1/2500 of a second to freeze them in flight without motion blur. I was using a 100mm-400mm zoom lens.  They only fed their young once about every 15-20 minutes despite it being 88 degrees, relatively calm, and sunny. Their feeding strategy is to bring in huge mouthfuls of tiny insects that caused their mouths to bulge on bottom (see photos). To get the photographic close-ups of the nest and nestlings, I placed an extension ladder against the chimney, climbed to the top of it, then aimed the camera with a flash and short telephoto lens down the chimney 72” to the nest. For these photos, I was using a 70mm-200mm zoom lens.  The biggest problem was that the chimney was so dark inside that I had trouble manually focusing the lens on the nest as did the camera when I switched to autofocus. In the nest photos, you can see there are 5 nestlings already crowding their tiny stick and saliva nest. Their eyes are still grown closed and their feather tracts are beginning to show. Notice in the one nest photo, that the old nest off to the side corner is starting to separate from the brick wall. In the close-ups of the twig nest, you can see the shiny, amber-colored glue, produced by the adults’ specialized saliva glands to adhere the twigs to each other and the entire nest to the bricks.

Observation Details: This morning I was greeted with another fledgling inside the building, hanging on a window screen.  I snapped a few quick photos, then was able to grab it and release it outdoors, and it flew away over Green Lake.   What followed was quite interesting...  The flying bird was soon joined by a couple of other swifts, and at one point there were four flying together – making swoops and circles not far away. I tried to shoot a few photos, and managed to get one that appeared to be the swift I had just released, since the picture shows that it has cobwebs trailing off its tail and wing! A couple of other photos showed birds that were obviously adults, due to the heavy feather molt in their wings. A few minutes later I watched as two of the swifts suddenly swooped down toward the building and plummeted down the chimney – separated by only about 2-3 feet!    I immediately went inside and shot a few photos up through the fireplace, and could tell that least one of the swifts that had dropped inside the chimney was the same captured/released fledgling that had cobwebs hanging from it!  Before I had been able to get set up to shoot photos, I’d heard some fluttering inside the chimney, so it’s possible that one of the birds that had dropped inside was an adult – but it may have taken off again before it could get any pictures.  Besides the fledgling that had cobwebs on it (which was clinging to the masonry), two nestlings were sitting on the nest, so it seemed unlikely that they had been ones that had just dropped inside the chimney.   Later the fledgling fluttered and moved up to where it ended up clinging onto the left side of the nest.

Observation Details: À mon arrivée, le carrousel est déjà bien formé. Compte tenu de l'heure à laquelle j'ai débuté le décompte, il est fort probable que certains oiseaux soient déjà à l'intérieur du dortoir pour y passer la nuit.  À partir de 20 h 48 m, en moins de dix (10) minutes, 164 individus entrent dans le dortoir. À mon départ, six (6) individus volent toujours à proximité... Comme c'est souvent le cas, sans doute que d'autres retardataires ont pu intégrer le dortoir au bénéfice de la pénombre ou de la nuit.  Au cours des quinze dernières années, il est arrivé à quelques occasions que j'aie le privilège d'observer 200-300 individus à ce dortoir... Sans doute que dans la région de l'Abitibi-Témiscamingue, ce dortoir est celui qui accueille le plus grand nombre de Martinets ramoneurs. C'est l'un des beaux dortoirs au Québec...  J'invite les Abitémiscamiennes et les Abitémiscamiens adeptes des loisirs ornithologiques à visiter ce dortoir afin d'y observer ces magnifiques phénomènes que sont les carrousels, tandis que la quantité de Martinets ramoneurs qui l'utilise y est relativement élevée... Le diminution croissante du nombre d'insectes et du nombre de sites de nidification disponibles et convenables pour l'espèce fait en sorte que bientôt, les carrousels pourraient être de moins en moins spectaculaires... Hélas!

Observation Details: A swarm of approximately 100 swifts circled above the Henry Houston school chimney in a loose vortex, and then a stream of swifts entered the chimney for the night. This is an interesting observation of communal roosting during spring migration in this species, which doesn't seem to occur every night like in the fall, but on sporadic spring nights when there happens to be enough birds traveling through together. I've had a couple other observations of this phenomenon at the HH school in years past.

Media notes: 5 nestling Chimney Swifts
Observation Details: I sat in the shade trying to photograph Chimney Swifts entering their brick chimney nest at 506 Erie Street. They flew so fast, it was almost impossible to react fast enough to trigger the shutter while they were in frame. My camera was on a tripod in the yard, triggered from across the yard with a remote. I had the camera’s shutter speed set at 1/2500 of a second to freeze them in flight without motion blur. I was using a 100mm-400mm zoom lens.  They only fed their young once about every 15-20 minutes despite it being 88 degrees, relatively calm, and sunny. Their feeding strategy is to bring in huge mouthfuls of tiny insects that caused their mouths to bulge on bottom (see photos). To get the photographic close-ups of the nest and nestlings, I placed an extension ladder against the chimney, climbed to the top of it, then aimed the camera with a flash and short telephoto lens down the chimney 72” to the nest. For these photos, I was using a 70mm-200mm zoom lens.  The biggest problem was that the chimney was so dark inside that I had trouble manually focusing the lens on the nest as did the camera when I switched to autofocus. In the nest photos, you can see there are 5 nestlings already crowding their tiny stick and saliva nest. Their eyes are still grown closed and their feather tracts are beginning to show. Notice in the one nest photo, that the old nest off to the side corner is starting to separate from the brick wall. In the close-ups of the twig nest, you can see the shiny, amber-colored glue, produced by the adults’ specialized saliva glands to adhere the twigs to each other and the entire nest to the bricks.

Repeated counts of these flying cigars. 28 initial count by 1s, however at one point a large group was visible above the tree line. Too large a group and too fast to allow for a reasonable count by 1s. Count was 40 when counted by 5s, and seems likely. Took the average of the two numbers here to get 34. Care was taken to be certain no other species were included in the count, which was easy as any swallows present mainly maintained a low elevation over the river while the majority of swifts maintained a higher elevation. Similar of events have occurred here year after year with larger groups of chimney swifts gathering over/around the Winooski River around and during rain events.

Observation Details: A large swirling flock of Chaetura that extended from The Chapel to the Lod Cook Hotel, but most were over the large trees next to the South Frat Lot. We spent most of the time on this list trying to sort through these birds and look for Vaux's. Tried to count them many times, but it was hard due to it being a swirling mass of swifts and swallows, so this is a rough count. We did on a few occasions get close to what we thought was a reliable 1x1 count, and most were in the low-mid 30s. Since most of the birds were backlit against the clouds, trying to identify them was challenging, and I'm not at all confident that we got all of them correct. Most of the birds appeared, to me, to show field marks of Chimney, including long heads and tails, fairly broad angular wings especially broad at the secondaries, and flew with deep somewhat rowing wing beats. Those times that the birds would fly in front of the trees, or lower to the ground, most birds had rather dark rumps and throats. Many photos to be added soon.

Media notes: Fledglings near nest.
Observation Details: Early this morning (6:04 to 6:07 AM) I re-visited the swift chimney, and initially spotted three fledglings hanging on the masonry near the nest.  I shot a few photos, then noticed that there was another bird also hanging near the nest – but this one appeared to be an adult.  My photo appears to show that its throat is distended – probably full of bugs.  I shot a video that included audio of one bird calling continuously, for a time – presumably the adult, perhaps agitated.  A moment later they all took flight, and disappeared – presumably up the chimney.  I shot one final photo of the empty nest site.    I went outdoors and observed swifts flying over the lake, not far away, with five in view at one point (three in one group, soon followed by two others).  I watched the area for about 15 minutes, and mostly the swifts were out of sight, but periodically I saw a few flying about overhead (along with several Barn Swallows passing by).

One swift was viewed for approximately 90 minutes, flying over the pond among a large mixed group of swallows (including Tree, Violet-green, Bank, Rough-winged, Barn and Cliff). When the swift came close, it seemed larger/bulkier than the surrounding swallows, slower and easier to track. It was dark grey-brown overall, with bulky wings. Wings long, inner primaries always bulging. Throat lighter than chest, rump close to same shade as back. One birder thought they heard it give loud single-note chirp calls every time it approached. However, no audio was recorded and with so many birds present, one can't be certain which bird was calling. Photos included, brief video here https://youtu.be/1QY1zFmTjOQ  More photos below.

Media notes: Nestlings at nest.
Observation Details: I returned to the fireplace/chimney this morning, and was somewhat relieved to find that there were no nestlings loose inside the building today.  When I first peered up inside the chimney, there were (as best I could tell) FOUR swifts present near the nest – clinging to the masonry.  Unfortunately a couple of them fluttered off before I was able to snap a photo, so I couldn’t know for sure what all of their ages were.  One of them may have been an adult, for it apparently left the chimney.  Another swift that had fluttered off was apparently perched on the masonry, in a spot where I couldn’t see it, but a little later it was back near the nest – and at that point there were THREE nestlings present.  Then it fluttered off and clung to the wall again – somewhere out of my view.  This seems to suggest that at least one of the two birds that I had previously released from the building (yesterday and the day before) had returned to the nest!  This is because there had originally been four nestlings present, and only two had been present on or near the nest yesterday, but today there were once again THREE nestlings at the nest.

The birds started gathering in numbers about 8 P.M., around the old, vacant Walley School. They circled the building chimney repeatedly, as some of the birds gradually peeled off and entered the chimney after 8:15 P.M.. The last swift was observed entering at 8:22 P.M.. The number above was obtained as I counted the individual birds entering. It was probable that I missed some birds, as some entered one right after another. Audio recordings are attached. The building has been vacant for over a decade.

Repeated counts of these flying cigars. 28 initial count by 1s, however at one point a large group was visible above the tree line. Too large a group and too fast to allow for a reasonable count by 1s. Count was 40 when counted by 5s, and seems likely. Took the average of the two numbers here to get 34. Care was taken to be certain no other species were included in the count, which was easy as any swallows present mainly maintained a low elevation over the river while the majority of swifts maintained a higher elevation. Similar of events have occurred here year after year with larger groups of chimney swifts gathering over/around the Winooski River around and during rain events.

This was an actual count, taken as the birds individually exited the former Walley School chimney before sunrise. The first bird exited at 5:28 A.M., but it was possible that others had already left before I started observing. I had heard the species in flight about 10 minutes earlier, while preparing to head to this location. All 70 birds were counted before any returned back to chimney. Media notes: Chimney Swift about to descend into a brick chimney containing its nest.  Notice its lower throat area bulging with insects for its young.
Observation Details: I sat in the shade trying to photograph Chimney Swifts entering their brick chimney nest at 506 Erie Street. They flew so fast, it was almost impossible to react fast enough to trigger the shutter while they were in frame. My camera was on a tripod in the yard, triggered from across the yard with a remote. I had the camera’s shutter speed set at 1/2500 of a second to freeze them in flight without motion blur. I was using a 100mm-400mm zoom lens.  They only fed their young once about every 15-20 minutes despite it being 88 degrees, relatively calm, and sunny. Their feeding strategy is to bring in huge mouthfuls of tiny insects that caused their mouths to bulge on bottom (see photos). To get the photographic close-ups of the nest and nestlings, I placed an extension ladder against the chimney, climbed to the top of it, then aimed the camera with a flash and short telephoto lens down the chimney 72” to the nest. For these photos, I was using a 70mm-200mm zoom lens.  The biggest problem was that the chimney was so dark inside that I had trouble manually focusing the lens on the nest as did the camera when I switched to autofocus. In the nest photos, you can see there are 5 nestlings already crowding their tiny stick and saliva nest. Their eyes are still grown closed and their feather tracts are beginning to show. Notice in the one nest photo, that the old nest off to the side corner is starting to separate from the brick wall. In the close-ups of the twig nest, you can see the shiny, amber-colored glue, produced by the adults’ specialized saliva glands to adhere the twigs to each other and the entire nest to the bricks.

Description by Emmett   After getting some great looks at the continuing male Hooded Warbler, we were standing in the parking lot of the Alpine County Sheriff’s Department when Aidan called out “swift!” I saw the bird naked eye and I had a jolt of excitement because it appeared large and long-winged and I thought it was going to be a Black Swift. I raised my binoculars and realized it was a Chaetura. I started yelling, “I think it’s a Chimney!” Luckily, Aidan Brubaker was able to get some great documentation shots of this bird over the brief minute long period of observation. Aidan’s initial impression of this bird before he saw it in bins was that it may be a WTSW.  The swift was flying maybe 30 meters off the ground and was flying north to south, it made one brief circle back before heading due south again. It was associating with a single Barn Swallow that it appeared slightly larger than. The flight style was a lot less fluttery than what I associate with a VASW and it appeared to glide with its wings bent back like a Black Swift. Plumage details were challenging to make out in the field but it appeared quite dark. Structurally it seemed to have long wings and tail.    In reviewing photos after our observation, the bird appears sooty colored and when the ventral side of the bird is evenly lit, appears to have minimal contrast between the breast and throat. No great photos of the rump were obtained but one shot seems to show less contrast than would be expected in a VASW (per S. Terrill & K. Garrett). The wings appear broad but the secondary bulge that is usually a good field mark for Chimney was only evident in some photos. The shape of the wing changes an incredible amount in each photo depending on the position it is in. The bird never vocalized.   Some of the notes that I received from Kimball Garrett:   The bird looks pretty dark and sooty in all of the photos (obviously lighting dependent, but I would have thought that this many photos of a Vaux's at different angles would at least sometimes show a much paler looking bird).  Along with overall darkness, I see little contrast between the throat and the dark underparts -- yes, the throat and chest is subtly paler, but not as pale as I'd expect on a Vaux's. The very first photo you attached also doesn't seem to show an especially pale rump area, so better for Chimney  To me Vaux's gives the impression of having the wings about mid body, with less sticking out behind that in a Chimney Swift (which, in turn, seems to have wings a bit farther forward, due mostly I presume to having a longer and more substantial tail). Your bird better matches Chimney in that regard.  I've never been especially convinced about the inner primary bulge of Chimney vs. Vaux's -- probably molt-dependent and can look very different in different flight angles and modes. But Chimney seems to have larger wings, i.e. relatively longer and broader-based compared to Vaux's; your photos look good for Chimney in this regard as well.   Kimball did add this as well, “I would be happy calling your bird a Chimney, but in the absence of vocal characters I guess I'm more in the 90% camp than the 100% camp.”   I have yet to hear back from all of the experts that I emailed these photos to but the consensus so far has varied between strongly suggestive of CHSW and “looks good” for CHSW. Based on their opinions from photos and our experience in the field I feel comfortable calling this bird as Alpine’s second Chimney Swift.

A “cigar with wings.” Shorter-tailed and longer-winged than a swallow, with more erratic, excited-Muppet-style flight. So definitely a swift, and while it’s a little early for a Chimney Swift, they’ve been recorded here this early before, and it seems much more likely to be a Chimney than any other kind of Swift. Size and plumage also seemed to match Chimney. But I know some have wondered whether it could be something else (just based on time of year) so I’m happy to change this ID if it turns out to be some sort of vagrant. Between Lefrak and the Peninsula. Photos.

Observation Details: Continuing. Maybe 2 (but birds were swiftly moving, flying out of view, and returning, so hard to keep track of individuals).  Several Vaux's were present for comparison. Chaetura larger than Vaux's and lankier, with longer wings and tail. Often flew below eye level, and then was noticeably darker overall than Vaux's, especially on the rump, which was only slightly paler than the back and upperwings, without sharp contrast. (When above eye level, all the Chaeturas were essentially silhouetted by the overcast sky and completely dark). Flight not as fluttery/batlike as Vaux's.  Heard staccato chattering call once. Bulging inner primaries.  Photos (but not confident that all photos are of the same bird).

The bird did a series of loops over the cemetery on 2 different occasions. Due to overcast it was impossible to make out subtle area of paleness (or lack thereof) in the field, though some processing of Karen's photos are indicative of CHSW. While we observed it, it immediately gave both Adam and myself the impression of CHSW over VASW due to perceived structure and the high amount of soaring/gliding it was doing and perhaps "easier" wingbeats compared to what we typically see in VASW, who seemingly have to put more work in to stay airborne. During its first appearance, it was fairly high and gave uninterrupted looks allowing for good study; the second time around it was quite low and would quickly disappear behind trees. Photos are consistent with our impressions in the field, though they cannot fully capture that.

Media notes: In this photo is a brooding adult looking ups at me.
Observation Details: For the past couple of months, I have been observing a pair of Chimney Swifts (Chaetura pelagica) flying in and out of the brick chimney at one of my rental houses in Edinboro, PA [Erie County].  I was pretty confident they had a nest in that chimney.  Today, a birding friend (Robert Scribner), and I put an extension ladder up and looked down into the chimney to verify nesting.  Just as I got to the top of the chimney, one of the parent swifts dove down into the chimney from the sky above, brushing the bill of my baseball cap.  Three others were circling high overhead and chattering.  Once I peered down into the dark chimney and my eyes adjusted, I could see their twig and saliva nest about 8 feet down [later measured to be exactly 72”].  It had 5 nestlings in it!  To build their nests, they break off very tiny twigs from the outer branches of trees as they fly past.  They glue the twigs into a nest using their glue-like saliva.  In one of these photos, a parent in clinging nearby looking up at me.  In the other, it is on the nest brooding the young.  Several times, the adult down in the chimney flapped its wings in such a way that it made a deep booming sound, apparently meant to scare me (a potential predator) away.  If you look carefully, you can see an older nest, attached in the corner of the chimney.  And there are 4 white, egg-like objects at the bottom of the chimney.  No doubt eggs from a previous nest that apparently got dislodged from heavy rains.  This is only the second swift nest I have ever observed by looking down a chimney.  The first was from New Hampshire in 1980.  It was in the egg stage.  Shortly after that 1980 photo was taken, one of the adults got hit by a car and killed.  In the photo I took of the dead adult, you can see the characteristic tail spines this species has, an adaptation for perching vertically.

Going in and out of a chimney periodically during midday. Could not see any food, but apparently it is nearly impossible to see when they carry it, so this must mean there is an active nest in there. Lots of chittering!

One swift was viewed for approximately 90 minutes, flying over the pond among a large mixed group of swallows (including Tree, Violet-green, Bank, Rough-winged, Barn and Cliff). When the swift came close, it seemed larger/bulkier than the surrounding swallows, slower and easier to track. It was dark grey-brown overall, with bulky wings. Wings long, inner primaries always bulging. Throat lighter than chest, rump close to same shade as back. One birder thought they heard it give loud single-note chirp calls every time it approached. However, no audio was recorded and with so many birds present, one can't be certain which bird was calling. Photos included, brief video here https://youtu.be/1QY1zFmTjOQ  More photos below.

Observation Details: Un premier individu repéré par hasard alors qu'il vole bas au dessus du garage au bout de la Rue Girard, silencieux. Circule autour du bout de la rue puis est rejoint par un deuxième individu. Rodent ensemble et font des allers et retours le long de la Rue Principale en criant quelques fois un crepitement. Silhouette unique de cigare, ailes longues et courbées par en arrière, bec minuscule, secondaires très courtes probablement en mue. Battement d'ailes très rapides suivis de courts vols planés, parfois les ailes tenues en l'air, rappellant vaguement un engoulevent. Retrouvés plus tard sur la Rue Principale, à mi chemin entre la Rue Girard et la Rue de l'Église. Il y a là deux vieilles maisons face à face avec chacune une très vieille cheminée en briques rouges. Les martinets tournent autour de ces maisons, volent parfois très bas et frôlent les toits, crient sans arrêt, font des paradent nuptiales ensemble fréquemment, sont même parfois agressifs avec moi en me volant juste au dessus de la tête. Un individu vu plus tard transporter une petite branche !

They repeatedly circled the large chimney at the vacant old Walley School. Periodically, some of the birds would peel off and enter the chimney. Media notes: Fledgling hanging on a window screen.
Observation Details: I returned to the chimney this morning to check the progress of the nest, and could see only three nestlings – so I figured that one of them had fledged.  I snapped a few photos (along with a little video that shows them stretching their wings), and then left them at peace.    As I was leaving I happened to notice that there was a Chimney Swift hanging on one of the window screens inside the building. This was actually a concern that I’d had a few days ago, wondering if it could happen that a fledgling might go DOWN into the fireplace, rather than UP the flue to exit the chimney.  Well, this apparently happened...  I shot a few photos of the fledgling hanging there, and of course wondered how long it had been there, and how hungry it might be – since I hadn’t been there for three days.  It could have happened earlier this morning, or who knows, the fledgling could have been there for a day or two?!   It was at the far end of the room from the fireplace, and it seemed unlikely that the parents had come down into the room to feed it there.  I was able to gently grab it and take it outside, and tried to hang the youngster on the outside of the chimney – but unfortunately it didn’t stay there, and it immediately took flight.  I watched it as it flew away, soon flying out over Green Lake, and I worried that it might drop down into the water.  But it seemed to fly pretty well, and I watched it making big circles up in the sky over the lake, until I lost it from view behind some trees.  Hopefully it will reunite with its parents and get something to eat!  The open fireplace certainly creates a risk for this to happen again with its siblings, so I’ll try to get over there daily to check for the same thing happening again...

This morning I was greeted with another fledgling inside the building, hanging on a window screen.  I snapped a few quick photos, then was able to grab it and release it outdoors, and it flew away over Green Lake.   What followed was quite interesting...  The flying bird was soon joined by a couple of other swifts, and at one point there were four flying together – making swoops and circles not far away. I tried to shoot a few photos, and managed to get one that appeared to be the swift I had just released, since the picture shows that it has cobwebs trailing off its tail and wing! A couple of other photos showed birds that were obviously adults, due to the heavy feather molt in their wings. A few minutes later I watched as two of the swifts suddenly swooped down toward the building and plummeted down the chimney – separated by only about 2-3 feet!    I immediately went inside and shot a few photos up through the fireplace, and could tell that least one of the swifts that had dropped inside the chimney was the same captured/released fledgling that had cobwebs hanging from it!  Before I had been able to get set up to shoot photos, I’d heard some fluttering inside the chimney, so it’s possible that one of the birds that had dropped inside was an adult – but it may have taken off again before it could get any pictures.  Besides the fledgling that had cobwebs on it (which was clinging to the masonry), two nestlings were sitting on the nest, so it seemed unlikely that they had been ones that had just dropped inside the chimney.   Later the fledgling fluttered and moved up to where it ended up clinging onto the left side of the nest.

I must confess, I blew this one. I was in Bonaparte's corner scanning the bay when out of the corner of my eye I noticed a swift barreling alongside me over Italian Slough. I popped it in binoculars and instantly went "oh my god that's a Chimney Swift" and started unzipping my backpack to get the camera out. It just looked really big, strong in flight, and dark through the rump (I first saw the dorsal side, and noticed no rump contrast). I refound the bird, zipping around, pretty steady in flight, not twinkling like a Vaux's, took some photos, watched it (as it was circling with the TRES at this point) and then took some more photos as it finally started to power away. My entire observation, I had remained pretty convinced I was looking at a CHSW. I lost it far over the parking lot, and instantly went to look at my photos, and went crap, I blew it. For some reason, my photos looked totally dark, blurry, messed up. I assumed there was nothing to be done, and then sort of talked my way out of the ID walking back to the car. I didn't have photos, anyway, so what was the point. A month or so later, I went to take photos off my camera, and realized--what I saw in the field clearly must have been a temporary issue with my monitor, because the photos are fine? AND they look damn good for a Chimney Swift! I sent them to a few friends with no context (all of them said Chimney, of course with the varying levels of hesitation that you typically expect here) and so now I don't know what to do with this bird. But here it is, caveat emptor. I do not count this on my personal list, at the moment, so do with that what you will...

Media notes: Oisillons au nid battant des ailes.
Observation Details: Durant la période précédent l'entrée d'un premier adulte, les oisillons ont faient plusieurs séances de battements d'ailes. À 19 h. 44 première observation alors qu'un adulte entre en flèche. Une seconde observation a lieu moins d'une minute plus tard avec l'entrée d'un second adulte. À ce moment là les deux adultes sont dans la cheminée. Les deux adultes sortent de la cheminée respectivement après avoir passés 1 min. 44 sec. et 1 min. 46 sec. à l'intérieur. Il est 19 h. 46. Le soleil se couche à 19 h. 56. L'intervalle avant la prochaine visite d'un adulte (presque 16 minutes) est meublé de plusieurs vocalises et de quelques séances de battements d'ailes. À 20 h. 01 la cinquième observation, est un adulte entrant en flèche. La sixième observation se déroule à 20 h. 04, les deux adultes sont de nouveaux ensemble dans la cheminée. À partir de ce moment, il y aura toujours un adulte dans la cheminée. À 20 h. 07 un adulte sort et s'envole vers le bas du village. La huitième observation se déroule à 20 h. 11 avec l'entrée en vrille d'un individu. Il s'écoulera 1 min. 40 sec. avant la sortie d'un adulte. Cette sortie à 20 h. 12 sera le dernier contacte visuel avec un martinet ramoneur et la neuvième observation. Il s'écoulera 24 minutes sans que je n'observe un martinet ramoneur. Durant cette séquence, les oisillons seront particulièrement bruyants cela étant dû, à mon humble avis, par la présence constante d'un des deux adultes à la cheminée. On distingue assez facilement durant ce segment, quelques séquences où l'adulte lance ses cliquetis singuliers. Sans en être certain à 100%, le spectrogramme laisse croire à une entrée du second adulte à 20 h. 21 min. Une entrée qui m'aurait échappée durant ma surveillance lors d'un mauvais clignement des yeux!. Une fois l'excitation passée cette dernière entrée, les 10 dernières minutes furent meublées par un enchaînements de séances de quémandages. La séance de surveillance se termine à 20 h. 33.

***1st Island Record As I got out of the truck I was immediately aware of a group of White-throated Swifts foraging and vocalizing overhead. I do not often see large groups of swifts continuously foraging here, so I paused to observe them. The first swift I looked at with binoculars was not a White-throated, but a Chaetura!!! The bird was dark overall, with a  paler throat and was bigger than the adjacent White-throated Swifts. Although timing and location supports Chimney over Vaux's, I figured my best bet at separating the two was to focus on getting photos. Photos show several field marks for Chimney, including the overall shape/structure, with the body appearing long behind the wings and the "bulge" in the primaries. Overall, its plumage was dark with little contrast except for the lighter colored throat. While foraging, the bird did often glide for seconds at a time, which I later learned is a habit of Chimney Swifts.
All doing courtship flights around the smaller building with the single chimney.  The larger building on the east end of the island has two chimneys.  I have seen them there as well.

Locality: Los Angeles River--Los Feliz golf course area
Observation Details: Continuing. Maybe 2 (but birds were swiftly moving, flying out of view, and returning, so hard to keep track of individuals).  Several Vaux's were present for comparison. Chaetura larger than Vaux's and lankier, with longer wings and tail. Often flew below eye level, and then was noticeably darker overall than Vaux's, especially on the rump, which was only slightly paler than the back and upperwings, without sharp contrast. (When above eye level, all the Chaeturas were essentially silhouetted by the overcast sky and completely dark). Flight not as fluttery/batlike as Vaux's.  Heard staccato chattering call once. Bulging inner primaries.  Photos (but not confident that all photos are of the same bird).

Record Accepted by AZ Bird Committee.  1)	Size: the bird did not appear noticeably smaller than the swallows in the same flock, suggesting Chimney Swift (VASW would be distinctly smaller than swallows);  2)	Wing shape: a distinct “primary bulge” is evident in many photos and was commented on in the field, suggesting Chimney Swift;  3)	Relative wing length: quantitative analysis of wing length and width shows these measurements to be outside of the range observed for Vaux’s Swift, but in the expected range for Chimney (ABC report has details);  4)	Rump color: this bird’s rump was not contrastingly lighter than the back, which is the expected pattern for Chimney;  5)	Color of underparts: the light gray throat transitioned abruptly to a much darker belly, which is a more expected pattern for Chimney;  6)	Terminal bar: the bird’s uppertail coverts appear in photos to reach the base of the tail barbs, this is expected for Chimney, but in Vaux’s the uppertail coverts would fall short of the base of the barbs.   Supporting media: A series of 38 photos can be found at https://flic.kr/s/aHsmc48nL5

Well, this apparently happened...  I shot a few photos of the fledgling hanging there, and of course wondered how long it had been there, and how hungry it might be – since I hadn’t been there for three days.  It could have happened earlier this morning, or who knows, the fledgling could have been there for a day or two?!   It was at the far end of the room from the fireplace, and it seemed unlikely that the parents had come down into the room to feed it there.  I was able to gently grab it and take it outside, and tried to hang the youngster on the outside of the chimney – but unfortunately it didn’t stay there, and it immediately took flight.  I watched it as it flew away, soon flying out over Green Lake, and I worried that it might drop down into the water.  But it seemed to fly pretty well, and I watched it making big circles up in the sky over the lake, until I lost it from view behind some trees.  Hopefully it will reunite with its parents and get something to eat!  The open fireplace certainly creates a risk for this to happen again with its siblings, so I’ll try to get over there daily to check for the same thing happening again...

Observation Details: À 5:49 un Martinet ramoneur est sorti seul silencieusement de la grande cheminée de briques rouges (48.566443,-69.234722) du flanc sud de la toiture de l'édifice municipal de Longue-Rive situé à côté de l'église, là où Eliza en avait vu un entrer hier soir. Il s'agit d'une grosse cheminée assez haute où l'espèce pourrait très bien nicher. Deux individus revus mélangés à des hirondelles en alimentation haut dans le ciel un peu plus bas dans le village vers l'est, à la hauteur de la ferme avec des chevaux. Facile à distinguer des hirondelles même à l'oeil nu, silhouette distinctive de cigare, ailes longues et minces arquées vers l'arrière. Font leur pepitement occasionnellement, mais plus difficile à percevoir par une journée venteuse comme aujourd'hui.

Un premier individu repéré par hasard alors qu'il vole bas au dessus du garage au bout de la Rue Girard, silencieux. Circule autour du bout de la rue puis est rejoint par un deuxième individu. Rodent ensemble et font des allers et retours le long de la Rue Principale en criant quelques fois un crepitement. Silhouette unique de cigare, ailes longues et courbées par en arrière, bec minuscule, secondaires très courtes probablement en mue. Battement d'ailes très rapides suivis de courts vols planés, parfois les ailes tenues en l'air, rappellant vaguement un engoulevent. Retrouvés plus tard sur la Rue Principale, à mi chemin entre la Rue Girard et la Rue de l'Église. Il y a là deux vieilles maisons face à face avec chacune une très vieille cheminée en briques rouges. Les martinets tournent autour de ces maisons, volent parfois très bas et frôlent les toits, crient sans arrêt, font des paradent nuptiales ensemble fréquemment, sont même parfois agressifs avec moi en me volant juste au dessus de la tête. Un individu vu plus tard transporter une petite branche !

Observation Details: In spite of the coastal and sea-faring birds, swifts might have made the most impressive appearance of the day. There was a large and steady flight throughout the afternoon, picking up in quantity towards sunset. CLR made concerted efforts to keep counting passing birds, but given the size of the flight, we would have been better off making multiple rate estimates. That said, this is likely a very conservative count as most of the CHSW flight was actually behind us (over the batture scrub or beyond the levee itself). I got the impression that they passed in loose "flocks" of birds, as we would often see a large dispersed mob amassing above the batture forest to our N and then leak out and stream SSW along the river edge. If a reasonable amount of time had passed, I would scan the levee and add this to the tally, which often resulted in counts of 50-100 CHSWs in a single scan.

Observation Details: ***1st Island Record As I got out of the truck I was immediately aware of a group of White-throated Swifts foraging and vocalizing overhead. I do not often see large groups of swifts continuously foraging here, so I paused to observe them. The first swift I looked at with binoculars was not a White-throated, but a Chaetura!!! The bird was dark overall, with a  paler throat and was bigger than the adjacent White-throated Swifts. Although timing and location supports Chimney over Vaux's, I figured my best bet at separating the two was to focus on getting photos. Photos show several field marks for Chimney, including the overall shape/structure, with the body appearing long behind the wings and the "bulge" in the primaries. Overall, its plumage was dark with little contrast except for the lighter colored throat. While foraging, the bird did often glide for seconds at a time, which I later learned is a habit of Chimney Swifts.

8 here 44.2602688, -65.7711051  4 here 44.2924769, -65.7471811  Possible roost site here 44.2958477, -65.7428192  At least 4 swifts were seen flying near and directly above a large hollow tree. No birds were seen entering or exiting the hollow tree, it just appeared to be a perfect roost site for them and they were flying above it. An image of the tree is attached to this email. I'm unsure of the species considering its state, but the size and lack of low branches could suggest pine. The diameter at breast height would have been roughly 2 feet.   Birds of North America Online has the following quote about Chimney Swifts:   "May forage some distance away from nest site; in New York State, some individuals foraged 3–6 km away (Fischer 1958)."  The closest man-made structures that I am aware of to the location of the tree/swifts are about 10 km away. This would suggest that they could be roosting/nesting in the woods rather than in man-made buildings, but I know this is rare now.  We did go to the base of the hollow tree and found that it was solid, so we couldn't look into it.  The coordinates were captured with my phone and should be accurate to within 10 m. It would be wonderful to try to confirm if they are actually using this dead tree. There is no mobile phone coverage there.  The logging roads can be accessed by several routes:  Langford Rd, https://goo.gl/maps/Ecx4o4ZLw142 Riverdale Rd, https://goo.gl/maps/9hz6oHRzuwN2 Gilberts Cove Rd, https://goo.gl/maps/LVwC1cYCEh92

As we approached Route 1 north from Rte 62 we saw a large flock of starlings with a swift very closely associating with it. It even tried to land on utility wires when they did. It was acting like one of their flock. We observed for close to half an hour from both the east and west sides of Route 1, just to get enough pics to hopefully ID to species if it turns out to be other than CHSW. After reviewing the photos our assessment of this bird is correct. We believe it is not a CHSW but do not know what else to call it. I thin this bird warrants  review by some experts. So we will send them off to someone to look at. The behavior of this bird was bizarre for a chimney swift, it was like  at times it thought it was a starling. When the starlings took off this bird would fly in with the flock. Like photographing a swift is not hard enough right! Where the starlings went this bird followed. I felt like ti’s flight style was not much off from a starling in some ways. It soared a lot, but maybe it was hungry/tired?  The way it soared the way it was hunting nothing seemed familiar. I was afraid it would get hit by a car because it was flying so low over RT 1 and maybe it did because we lost it and could not relocate it but we did re-find the flock of starlings.  The head to me is not like a CHSW, it is chunky much more dominant/wider than CHSW. A CHSW has a sickle like wing with the front edge curving, this bird has a more straight leading edge and it is evident in almost all the photos. To me CHSW look just like “they” say a cigar with wings, this bird clearly does not look like that to me. It looks almost more swallow like and in fact acted more swallow like.

Media notes: 600+ birds coming into roost in school chimney.  70°F, overcast, high cloud ceiling, winds 3-5 mph. 600+ individuals arriving at evening roost in chimney of Belle Sherman School.   Birds began arriving in small numbers then swelling to a flock of over 600 birds flying in a circular pattern over the chimney.  The birds circled the chimney in a clockwise fashion, with the chimney at the NE edge of their circle.  The estimated count was made at the time the flock appeared most dense.  The flock spiraled for several minutes and then rapidly descended into the chimney.  Wing sounds and vocalizations in close proximity to the microphones, birds at times within inches of the microphones, are obvious at this point in the recording.  Vocalizations from the birds inside the chimney are most obvious at 12:52 into the recording (incl. the catalog number announcement) and sound somewhat different from the calls given in flight.  The record level of the Nagra was increased at the end of the recording to provide a higher signal level of the "in-chimney" vocalizations. Other Behaviors: Flight Sound, Perch. Equipment Notes: Nagra IV-SD in Music and Low Frequency Attentuation (M and LFA) and Stereo High Sensitivity (STHS) settings.  An X-Y pair of Sennheiser MKH 106T omnidirectional microphones on a stereo bar were hoisted up to the very edge of the chimney.  Two Sennheiser BP2 power modules set in "Cut" (low frequency attenuation) mode were used to power the microphones.

Report of a distressed bird by Summit Dorm where construction occurring on campus. Discovered a chimney swift on the ground.  Three swifts detected flying between Summit and Sterling Dorm.  Took the CHSW home to rest before trying to release again or take to rehab the next day.  Returned CHSW to area about 2 hours later.  Noticed five chimney swifts about Calhoun School house flying over building and then going into a chimney on my way to attempt release.  Noticed two of the three swifts still foraging  by dorms going into chimney of Summit Dorm..  Tried to release swift I had held for a few hours.  Successful release of previously distressed swift.  A lot of construction by dorms with tall trucks so perhaps flew into something.  Nine different swifts (including distressed bird) detected in total.   Swifts still on campus in July and it is important to note that each summer nestlings where heard in at least one of the chimneys (Sterling Dorm) when I used to live until last summer.  Unfortunately, despite my encouragement not to cap the chimney in Sterling, the new faculty insisted as afraid of birds and chimney was capped last fall.  My students and I will be building a Chimney Roost to place on campus this coming academic year to make-up for lost nesting space.

Locality: Dairy Mart Road--Tijuana River/sod farm (view from road only)
Observation Details: The Chimney Swift appeared at precisely 6:45am flying in from northwest direction from the Dairy Mart Pond area where Dave Povey had seen it flying a bit earlier. Some 5-10 minutes later Vaux's Swift began to arrive to make up a group about 10 birds in total.  I left about 8:20am and bird still present. Watched by several observers this morning.  The Chimney Swift appeared slightly larger in size than nearby Vaux's Swift with larger primary bulge after the secondaries and larger primary wing shape visible in many angles and not only when wing flexed wide open. Also more uniformly dark in coloration with small contrast in the upperparts, pale throat patch noticeable against darker belly, face rather aggressive looking with fine white line above and stopping just forward of the eye visible. Underparts quite dark and could be picked out readily from paler Vaux's especially when green willow trees in the background.  Flight style was noticeably different from the Vaux's with slightly slower flapping but more powerful looking flight generation than twittery haywire flight energy of the Vaux's.  Also, as other observers noted, the Chimney Swift taking long continuous glides in horizontal flight across the feeding area of the swifts. In addition did seem to often appear a bit higher in the sky more regularly.  Feather wear apparent and matches photos taken by yesterday's observers.

Additional observation notes on twig gathering behavior: Photos show twigs being grabbed initially in bill and held there during flight away. Horizontal flight, through the group of twigs which were in general towards the top of a 20-30 ft. tree. The speed was enough that I had no time to specifically focus/shoot, it was a blind moving shot(s) during the pass. I do have one photo of wings in a V but not sure if that was typical during the passes.

One swift was viewed for approximately 90 minutes, flying over the pond among a large mixed group of swallows (including Tree, Violet-green, Bank, Rough-winged, Barn and Cliff). When the swift came close, it seemed larger/bulkier than the surrounding swallows, slower and easier to track. It was dark grey-brown overall, with bulky wings. Wings long, inner primaries always bulging. Throat lighter than chest, rump close to same shade as back. One birder thought they heard it give loud single-note chirp calls every time it approached. However, no audio was recorded and with so many birds present, one can't be certain which bird was calling. Photos included, brief video here https://youtu.be/1QY1zFmTjOQ  More photos below.

Observation Details: ***1st Island Record As I got out of the truck I was immediately aware of a group of White-throated Swifts foraging and vocalizing overhead. I do not often see large groups of swifts continuously foraging here, so I paused to observe them. The first swift I looked at with binoculars was not a White-throated, but a Chaetura!!! The bird was dark overall, with a  paler throat and was bigger than the adjacent White-throated Swifts. Although timing and location supports Chimney over Vaux's, I figured my best bet at separating the two was to focus on getting photos. Photos show several field marks for Chimney, including the overall shape/structure, with the body appearing long behind the wings and the "bulge" in the primaries. Overall, its plumage was dark with little contrast except for the lighter colored throat. While foraging, the bird did often glide for seconds at a time, which I later learned is a habit of Chimney Swifts.

Description by Emmett   After getting some great looks at the continuing male Hooded Warbler, we were standing in the parking lot of the Alpine County Sheriff’s Department when Aidan called out “swift!” I saw the bird naked eye and I had a jolt of excitement because it appeared large and long-winged and I thought it was going to be a Black Swift. I raised my binoculars and realized it was a Chaetura. I started yelling, “I think it’s a Chimney!” Luckily, Aidan Brubaker was able to get some great documentation shots of this bird over the brief minute long period of observation. Aidan’s initial impression of this bird before he saw it in bins was that it may be a WTSW.  The swift was flying maybe 30 meters off the ground and was flying north to south, it made one brief circle back before heading due south again. It was associating with a single Barn Swallow that it appeared slightly larger than. The flight style was a lot less fluttery than what I associate with a VASW and it appeared to glide with its wings bent back like a Black Swift. Plumage details were challenging to make out in the field but it appeared quite dark. Structurally it seemed to have long wings and tail.    In reviewing photos after our observation, the bird appears sooty colored and when the ventral side of the bird is evenly lit, appears to have minimal contrast between the breast and throat. No great photos of the rump were obtained but one shot seems to show less contrast than would be expected in a VASW (per S. Terrill & K. Garrett). The wings appear broad but the secondary bulge that is usually a good field mark for Chimney was only evident in some photos. The shape of the wing changes an incredible amount in each photo depending on the position it is in. The bird never vocalized.   Some of the notes that I received from Kimball Garrett:   The bird looks pretty dark and sooty in all of the photos (obviously lighting dependent, but I would have thought that this many photos of a Vaux's at different angles would at least sometimes show a much paler looking bird).  Along with overall darkness, I see little contrast between the throat and the dark underparts -- yes, the throat and chest is subtly paler, but not as pale as I'd expect on a Vaux's. The very first photo you attached also doesn't seem to show an especially pale rump area, so better for Chimney  To me Vaux's gives the impression of having the wings about mid body, with less sticking out behind that in a Chimney Swift (which, in turn, seems to have wings a bit farther forward, due mostly I presume to having a longer and more substantial tail). Your bird better matches Chimney in that regard.  I've never been especially convinced about the inner primary bulge of Chimney vs. Vaux's -- probably molt-dependent and can look very different in different flight angles and modes. But Chimney seems to have larger wings, i.e. relatively longer and broader-based compared to Vaux's; your photos look good for Chimney in this regard as well.   Kimball did add this as well, “I would be happy calling your bird a Chimney, but in the absence of vocal characters I guess I'm more in the 90% camp than the 100% camp.”   I have yet to hear back from all of the experts that I emailed these photos to but the consensus so far has varied between strongly suggestive of CHSW and “looks good” for CHSW. Based on their opinions from photos and our experience in the field I feel comfortable calling this bird as Alpine’s second Chimney Swift.

Media notes: Chimney Swift about to descend into a brick chimney containing its nest.  Notice its lower throat area bulging with insects for its young.
Observation Details: I sat in the shade trying to photograph Chimney Swifts entering their brick chimney nest at 506 Erie Street. They flew so fast, it was almost impossible to react fast enough to trigger the shutter while they were in frame. My camera was on a tripod in the yard, triggered from across the yard with a remote. I had the camera’s shutter speed set at 1/2500 of a second to freeze them in flight without motion blur. I was using a 100mm-400mm zoom lens.  They only fed their young once about every 15-20 minutes despite it being 88 degrees, relatively calm, and sunny. Their feeding strategy is to bring in huge mouthfuls of tiny insects that caused their mouths to bulge on bottom (see photos). To get the photographic close-ups of the nest and nestlings, I placed an extension ladder against the chimney, climbed to the top of it, then aimed the camera with a flash and short telephoto lens down the chimney 72” to the nest. For these photos, I was using a 70mm-200mm zoom lens.  The biggest problem was that the chimney was so dark inside that I had trouble manually focusing the lens on the nest as did the camera when I switched to autofocus. In the nest photos, you can see there are 5 nestlings already crowding their tiny stick and saliva nest. Their eyes are still grown closed and their feather tracts are beginning to show. Notice in the one nest photo, that the old nest off to the side corner is starting to separate from the brick wall. In the close-ups of the twig nest, you can see the shiny, amber-colored glue, produced by the adults’ specialized saliva glands to adhere the twigs to each other and the entire nest to the bricks.

I must confess, I blew this one. I was in Bonaparte's corner scanning the bay when out of the corner of my eye I noticed a swift barreling alongside me over Italian Slough. I popped it in binoculars and instantly went "oh my god that's a Chimney Swift" and started unzipping my backpack to get the camera out. It just looked really big, strong in flight, and dark through the rump (I first saw the dorsal side, and noticed no rump contrast). I refound the bird, zipping around, pretty steady in flight, not twinkling like a Vaux's, took some photos, watched it (as it was circling with the TRES at this point) and then took some more photos as it finally started to power away. My entire observation, I had remained pretty convinced I was looking at a CHSW. I lost it far over the parking lot, and instantly went to look at my photos, and went crap, I blew it. For some reason, my photos looked totally dark, blurry, messed up. I assumed there was nothing to be done, and then sort of talked my way out of the ID walking back to the car. I didn't have photos, anyway, so what was the point. A month or so later, I went to take photos off my camera, and realized--what I saw in the field clearly must have been a temporary issue with my monitor, because the photos are fine? AND they look damn good for a Chimney Swift! I sent them to a few friends with no context (all of them said Chimney, of course with the varying levels of hesitation that you typically expect here) and so now I don't know what to do with this bird. But here it is, caveat emptor. I do not count this on my personal list, at the moment, so do with that what you will...

Record Accepted by AZ Bird Committee.  1)	Size: the bird did not appear noticeably smaller than the swallows in the same flock, suggesting Chimney Swift (VASW would be distinctly smaller than swallows);  2)	Wing shape: a distinct “primary bulge” is evident in many photos and was commented on in the field, suggesting Chimney Swift;  3)	Relative wing length: quantitative analysis of wing length and width shows these measurements to be outside of the range observed for Vaux’s Swift, but in the expected range for Chimney (ABC report has details);  4)	Rump color: this bird’s rump was not contrastingly lighter than the back, which is the expected pattern for Chimney;  5)	Color of underparts: the light gray throat transitioned abruptly to a much darker belly, which is a more expected pattern for Chimney;  6)	Terminal bar: the bird’s uppertail coverts appear in photos to reach the base of the tail barbs, this is expected for Chimney, but in Vaux’s the uppertail coverts would fall short of the base of the barbs.   Supporting media: A series of 38 photos can be found at https://flic.kr/s/aHsmc48nL5

The bird did a series of loops over the cemetery on 2 different occasions. Due to overcast it was impossible to make out subtle area of paleness (or lack thereof) in the field, though some processing of Karen's photos are indicative of CHSW. While we observed it, it immediately gave both Adam and myself the impression of CHSW over VASW due to perceived structure and the high amount of soaring/gliding it was doing and perhaps "easier" wingbeats compared to what we typically see in VASW, who seemingly have to put more work in to stay airborne. During its first appearance, it was fairly high and gave uninterrupted looks allowing for good study; the second time around it was quite low and would quickly disappear behind trees. Photos are consistent with our impressions in the field, though they cannot fully capture that.

Description by Emmett   After getting some great looks at the continuing male Hooded Warbler, we were standing in the parking lot of the Alpine County Sheriff’s Department when Aidan called out “swift!” I saw the bird naked eye and I had a jolt of excitement because it appeared large and long-winged and I thought it was going to be a Black Swift. I raised my binoculars and realized it was a Chaetura. I started yelling, “I think it’s a Chimney!” Luckily, Aidan Brubaker was able to get some great documentation shots of this bird over the brief minute long period of observation. Aidan’s initial impression of this bird before he saw it in bins was that it may be a WTSW.  The swift was flying maybe 30 meters off the ground and was flying north to south, it made one brief circle back before heading due south again. It was associating with a single Barn Swallow that it appeared slightly larger than. The flight style was a lot less fluttery than what I associate with a VASW and it appeared to glide with its wings bent back like a Black Swift. Plumage details were challenging to make out in the field but it appeared quite dark. Structurally it seemed to have long wings and tail.    In reviewing photos after our observation, the bird appears sooty colored and when the ventral side of the bird is evenly lit, appears to have minimal contrast between the breast and throat. No great photos of the rump were obtained but one shot seems to show less contrast than would be expected in a VASW (per S. Terrill & K. Garrett). The wings appear broad but the secondary bulge that is usually a good field mark for Chimney was only evident in some photos. The shape of the wing changes an incredible amount in each photo depending on the position it is in. The bird never vocalized.   Some of the notes that I received from Kimball Garrett:   The bird looks pretty dark and sooty in all of the photos (obviously lighting dependent, but I would have thought that this many photos of a Vaux's at different angles would at least sometimes show a much paler looking bird).  Along with overall darkness, I see little contrast between the throat and the dark underparts -- yes, the throat and chest is subtly paler, but not as pale as I'd expect on a Vaux's. The very first photo you attached also doesn't seem to show an especially pale rump area, so better for Chimney  To me Vaux's gives the impression of having the wings about mid body, with less sticking out behind that in a Chimney Swift (which, in turn, seems to have wings a bit farther forward, due mostly I presume to having a longer and more substantial tail). Your bird better matches Chimney in that regard.  I've never been especially convinced about the inner primary bulge of Chimney vs. Vaux's -- probably molt-dependent and can look very different in different flight angles and modes. But Chimney seems to have larger wings, i.e. relatively longer and broader-based compared to Vaux's; your photos look good for Chimney in this regard as well.   Kimball did add this as well, “I would be happy calling your bird a Chimney, but in the absence of vocal characters I guess I'm more in the 90% camp than the 100% camp.”   I have yet to hear back from all of the experts that I emailed these photos to but the consensus so far has varied between strongly suggestive of CHSW and “looks good” for CHSW. Based on their opinions from photos and our experience in the field I feel comfortable calling this bird as Alpine’s second Chimney Swift.

*** consensus is Chimney Swift.  One strange looking swift-type bird associating with the Tree Swallows.  Much different wing shape that were not nearly as thin as a Chimney Swift, very pale almost white throat, and a very very pale rump which was buffy or very light tan colored. There was some brownish tint to the upper back and base of wings, and there was a light color to the forewings at the alula.  Overall it seemed broader/flatter than a Chimney Swift, with wings that had a much wider chord from leading to trailing edge. The bird had a dark forehead. Locality: Dairy Mart Road--Tijuana River/sod farm (view from road only)
Observation Details: The Chimney Swift appeared at precisely 6:45am flying in from northwest direction from the Dairy Mart Pond area where Dave Povey had seen it flying a bit earlier. Some 5-10 minutes later Vaux's Swift began to arrive to make up a group about 10 birds in total.  I left about 8:20am and bird still present. Watched by several observers this morning.  The Chimney Swift appeared slightly larger in size than nearby Vaux's Swift with larger primary bulge after the secondaries and larger primary wing shape visible in many angles and not only when wing flexed wide open. Also more uniformly dark in coloration with small contrast in the upperparts, pale throat patch noticeable against darker belly, face rather aggressive looking with fine white line above and stopping just forward of the eye visible. Underparts quite dark and could be picked out readily from paler Vaux's especially when green willow trees in the background.  Flight style was noticeably different from the Vaux's with slightly slower flapping but more powerful looking flight generation than twittery haywire flight energy of the Vaux's.  Also, as other observers noted, the Chimney Swift taking long continuous glides in horizontal flight across the feeding area of the swifts. In addition did seem to often appear a bit higher in the sky more regularly.  Feather wear apparent and matches photos taken by yesterday's observers.

In spite of the coastal and sea-faring birds, swifts might have made the most impressive appearance of the day. There was a large and steady flight throughout the afternoon, picking up in quantity towards sunset. CLR made concerted efforts to keep counting passing birds, but given the size of the flight, we would have been better off making multiple rate estimates. That said, this is likely a very conservative count as most of the CHSW flight was actually behind us (over the batture scrub or beyond the levee itself). I got the impression that they passed in loose "flocks" of birds, as we would often see a large dispersed mob amassing above the batture forest to our N and then leak out and stream SSW along the river edge. If a reasonable amount of time had passed, I would scan the levee and add this to the tally, which often resulted in counts of 50-100 CHSWs in a single scan.

Observation Details: As we approached Route 1 north from Rte 62 we saw a large flock of starlings with a swift very closely associating with it. It even tried to land on utility wires when they did. It was acting like one of their flock. We observed for close to half an hour from both the east and west sides of Route 1, just to get enough pics to hopefully ID to species if it turns out to be other than CHSW. After reviewing the photos our assessment of this bird is correct. We believe it is not a CHSW but do not know what else to call it. I thin this bird warrants  review by some experts. So we will send them off to someone to look at. The behavior of this bird was bizarre for a chimney swift, it was like  at times it thought it was a starling. When the starlings took off this bird would fly in with the flock. Like photographing a swift is not hard enough right! Where the starlings went this bird followed. I felt like ti’s flight style was not much off from a starling in some ways. It soared a lot, but maybe it was hungry/tired?  The way it soared the way it was hunting nothing seemed familiar. I was afraid it would get hit by a car because it was flying so low over RT 1 and maybe it did because we lost it and could not relocate it but we did re-find the flock of starlings.  The head to me is not like a CHSW, it is chunky much more dominant/wider than CHSW. A CHSW has a sickle like wing with the front edge curving, this bird has a more straight leading edge and it is evident in almost all the photos. To me CHSW look just like “they” say a cigar with wings, this bird clearly does not look like that to me. It looks almost more swallow like and in fact acted more swallow like.

Those numbers increased to scores, then hundreds then thousands as we approached sunset at 7:35.    The Swifts formed a vortex around the stack and the diameter of the vortex contracted as the sky got darker.  At 8:00 the Swifts started entering the stack.  By 8:07 the sky was clear of birds.  Final estimate 3200.

***1st Island Record As I got out of the truck I was immediately aware of a group of White-throated Swifts foraging and vocalizing overhead. I do not often see large groups of swifts continuously foraging here, so I paused to observe them. The first swift I looked at with binoculars was not a White-throated, but a Chaetura!!! The bird was dark overall, with a  paler throat and was bigger than the adjacent White-throated Swifts. Although timing and location supports Chimney over Vaux's, I figured my best bet at separating the two was to focus on getting photos. Photos show several field marks for Chimney, including the overall shape/structure, with the body appearing long behind the wings and the "bulge" in the primaries. Overall, its plumage was dark with little contrast except for the lighter colored throat. While foraging, the bird did often glide for seconds at a time, which I later learned is a habit of Chimney Swifts.

Media notes: In this photo it is evident that the uppertail coverts extend all the way to the base of the barbs at the end of the tail. In Vaux's Swift, the uppertail coverts fall 2-4mm short of the base of the barbs, leaving an evident "terminal bar" where the tail extends past the uppertail coverts. See here for a comparative example from VASW: https://macaulaylibrary.org/asset/97753901
Observation Details: Record Accepted by AZ Bird Committee.  1)	Size: the bird did not appear noticeably smaller than the swallows in the same flock, suggesting Chimney Swift (VASW would be distinctly smaller than swallows);  2)	Wing shape: a distinct “primary bulge” is evident in many photos and was commented on in the field, suggesting Chimney Swift;  3)	Relative wing length: quantitative analysis of wing length and width shows these measurements to be outside of the range observed for Vaux’s Swift, but in the expected range for Chimney (ABC report has details);  4)	Rump color: this bird’s rump was not contrastingly lighter than the back, which is the expected pattern for Chimney;  5)	Color of underparts: the light gray throat transitioned abruptly to a much darker belly, which is a more expected pattern for Chimney;  6)	Terminal bar: the bird’s uppertail coverts appear in photos to reach the base of the tail barbs, this is expected for Chimney, but in Vaux’s the uppertail coverts would fall short of the base of the barbs.   Supporting media: A series of 38 photos can be found at https://flic.kr/s/aHsmc48nL5

Observation Details: Approximate number. Swifts were circling this chimney at a three-story house, 8121 Glenbrittle Way. They were making these chirping noises but they were SILENT when they began to enter the chimney as a swirling flock at 19:40. It took about five minutes to complete the roosting. The CHSW used this chimney in the fall of 2016 and 2015 as well. Note: The homeowners know about the CHSW and they don't mind the use of their chimney. The owners and the neighbor who discovered the roosing tower (Hal Marcus) are certain that CHSW had never used this chimney for fall roosting, prior to the fall of 2015. I also noted that a home with a large stone chimney was torn down in early 2015 (8341 Old Lead Mine Road, an address that does not exist any more) to make way for a large development.The destroyed house was a very short distance from this current roosting chimney.  I believe the CHSW were using the stone chimney at 8341 Old Lead Mine as a roosting tower during fall migration prior to 2015, and made the switch to 8121 Glenbrittle Way when they returned in the fall of 2015 to find their roosting spot gone.

Observation Details: Three fledglings were near the nest this morning, and I took several photos up into the fireplace (photos attached).  After I went outside I watched the chimney for a little while.  One bird dropped in at 6:35 am. -- probably an adult??  Begging calls could be heard for a short time, emanating from the chimney.  The bird left again at 6:38, dropping low from chimney over the roof, to the north, as I'd seen before.  It headed out over the lake, disappearing from sight.

Media notes: Nestlings at nest.
Observation Details: I returned to the fireplace/chimney this morning, and was somewhat relieved to find that there were no nestlings loose inside the building today.  When I first peered up inside the chimney, there were (as best I could tell) FOUR swifts present near the nest – clinging to the masonry.  Unfortunately a couple of them fluttered off before I was able to snap a photo, so I couldn’t know for sure what all of their ages were.  One of them may have been an adult, for it apparently left the chimney.  Another swift that had fluttered off was apparently perched on the masonry, in a spot where I couldn’t see it, but a little later it was back near the nest – and at that point there were THREE nestlings present.  Then it fluttered off and clung to the wall again – somewhere out of my view.  This seems to suggest that at least one of the two birds that I had previously released from the building (yesterday and the day before) had returned to the nest!  This is because there had originally been four nestlings present, and only two had been present on or near the nest yesterday, but today there were once again THREE nestlings at the nest.

Observation Details: Description by Emmett   After getting some great looks at the continuing male Hooded Warbler, we were standing in the parking lot of the Alpine County Sheriff’s Department when Aidan called out “swift!” I saw the bird naked eye and I had a jolt of excitement because it appeared large and long-winged and I thought it was going to be a Black Swift. I raised my binoculars and realized it was a Chaetura. I started yelling, “I think it’s a Chimney!” Luckily, Aidan Brubaker was able to get some great documentation shots of this bird over the brief minute long period of observation. Aidan’s initial impression of this bird before he saw it in bins was that it may be a WTSW.  The swift was flying maybe 30 meters off the ground and was flying north to south, it made one brief circle back before heading due south again. It was associating with a single Barn Swallow that it appeared slightly larger than. The flight style was a lot less fluttery than what I associate with a VASW and it appeared to glide with its wings bent back like a Black Swift. Plumage details were challenging to make out in the field but it appeared quite dark. Structurally it seemed to have long wings and tail.    In reviewing photos after our observation, the bird appears sooty colored and when the ventral side of the bird is evenly lit, appears to have minimal contrast between the breast and throat. No great photos of the rump were obtained but one shot seems to show less contrast than would be expected in a VASW (per S. Terrill & K. Garrett). The wings appear broad but the secondary bulge that is usually a good field mark for Chimney was only evident in some photos. The shape of the wing changes an incredible amount in each photo depending on the position it is in. The very first photo you attached also doesn't seem to show an especially pale rump area, so better for Chimney  To me Vaux's gives the impression of having the wings about mid body, with less sticking out behind that in a Chimney Swift (which, in turn, seems to have wings a bit farther forward, due mostly I presume to having a longer and more substantial tail). Your bird better matches Chimney in that regard.  I've never been especially convinced about the inner primary bulge of Chimney vs. Vaux's -- probably molt-dependent and can look very different in different flight angles and modes. But Chimney seems to have larger wings, i.e. relatively longer and broader-based compared to Vaux's; your photos look good for Chimney in this regard as well.   Kimball did add this as well, “I would be happy calling your bird a Chimney, but in the absence of vocal characters I guess I'm more in the 90% camp than the 100% camp.”   I have yet to hear back from all of the experts that I emailed these photos to but the consensus so far has varied between strongly suggestive of CHSW and “looks good” for CHSW. Based on their opinions from photos and our experience in the field I feel comfortable calling this bird as Alpine’s second Chimney Swift.

Observation Details: In spite of the coastal and sea-faring birds, swifts might have made the most impressive appearance of the day. There was a large and steady flight throughout the afternoon, picking up in quantity towards sunset. CLR made concerted efforts to keep counting passing birds, but given the size of the flight, we would have been better off making multiple rate estimates. That said, this is likely a very conservative count as most of the CHSW flight was actually behind us (over the batture scrub or beyond the levee itself). I got the impression that they passed in loose "flocks" of birds, as we would often see a large dispersed mob amassing above the batture forest to our N and then leak out and stream SSW along the river edge. If a reasonable amount of time had passed, I would scan the levee and add this to the tally, which often resulted in counts of 50-100 CHSWs in a single scan.

Observation Details: Very rare and would represent just second county record I believe if accepted. Initially picked up while driving slowly down water street and seemed like a somewhat odd chaetura swift. Pulled over and was immediately struck by its overall large size compared to nearby tree swallows, seeming to be about the size of the swallows or slightly smaller and overall dark coloration. We then decided to watch the bird for the next 10 or so minutes as it repeatedly circled this house (41.8594295, -120.1525653), likely a roosting region. Besides the size and overall color, the bird stood out in having relatively dark throat contrasting very slightly woth breast, dark grayish rump nearly the same tone as the back, broad wings, and overall dark charcoly body color. The bird’s flight differed from Vaux’s seen 10 minutes later in being slower, less flicky and less erratic, with longer periods of gliding mixed in. The bird was undergoing active primary molt, with the inner 2-3 prinaries coming in. The wings were broad but did not have as noticeable of a “secondary bulge” as is present in certain individuals of this species. We played for both chimney and vaux’s swift but the bird never vocalized, though it came in to chimney playback and circled low overhead. Field notes made while observing bird (rest of notes came c 15 mins later): Charcoly, large (size of tres), rump only very slightly lighter than back and barely contrasting, throat slightly contrasting. Lots of gliding, interspersed with choppy wingbeats. Flight relatively direct.
