Description by Emmett   After getting some great looks at the continuing male Hooded Warbler, we were standing in the parking lot of the Alpine County Sheriff’s Department when Aidan called out “swift!” I saw the bird naked eye and I had a jolt of excitement because it appeared large and long-winged and I thought it was going to be a Black Swift. I raised my binoculars and realized it was a Chaetura. I started yelling, “I think it’s a Chimney!” Luckily, Aidan Brubaker was able to get some great documentation shots of this bird over the brief minute long period of observation. Aidan’s initial impression of this bird before he saw it in bins was that it may be a WTSW.  The swift was flying maybe 30 meters off the ground and was flying north to south, it made one brief circle back before heading due south again. It was associating with a single Barn Swallow that it appeared slightly larger than. The flight style was a lot less fluttery than what I associate with a VASW and it appeared to glide with its wings bent back like a Black Swift. Plumage details were challenging to make out in the field but it appeared quite dark. Structurally it seemed to have long wings and tail.    In reviewing photos after our observation, the bird appears sooty colored and when the ventral side of the bird is evenly lit, appears to have minimal contrast between the breast and throat. No great photos of the rump were obtained but one shot seems to show less contrast than would be expected in a VASW (per S. Terrill & K. Garrett). The wings appear broad but the secondary bulge that is usually a good field mark for Chimney was only evident in some photos. The shape of the wing changes an incredible amount in each photo depending on the position it is in. The bird never vocalized.   Some of the notes that I received from Kimball Garrett:   The bird looks pretty dark and sooty in all of the photos (obviously lighting dependent, but I would have thought that this many photos of a Vaux's at different angles would at least sometimes show a much paler looking bird).  Along with overall darkness, I see little contrast between the throat and the dark underparts -- yes, the throat and chest is subtly paler, but not as pale as I'd expect on a Vaux's. The very first photo you attached also doesn't seem to show an especially pale rump area, so better for Chimney  To me Vaux's gives the impression of having the wings about mid body, with less sticking out behind that in a Chimney Swift (which, in turn, seems to have wings a bit farther forward, due mostly I presume to having a longer and more substantial tail). Your bird better matches Chimney in that regard.  I've never been especially convinced about the inner primary bulge of Chimney vs. Vaux's -- probably molt-dependent and can look very different in different flight angles and modes. But Chimney seems to have larger wings, i.e. relatively longer and broader-based compared to Vaux's; your photos look good for Chimney in this regard as well.   Kimball did add this as well, “I would be happy calling your bird a Chimney, but in the absence of vocal characters I guess I'm more in the 90% camp than the 100% camp.”   I have yet to hear back from all of the experts that I emailed these photos to but the consensus so far has varied between strongly suggestive of CHSW and “looks good” for CHSW. Based on their opinions from photos and our experience in the field I feel comfortable calling this bird as Alpine’s second Chimney Swift.

Media notes: Chimney Swift about to descend into a brick chimney containing its nest.
Observation Details: I sat in the shade trying to photograph Chimney Swifts entering their brick chimney nest at 506 Erie Street. They flew so fast, it was almost impossible to react fast enough to trigger the shutter while they were in frame. My camera was on a tripod in the yard, triggered from across the yard with a remote. I had the camera’s shutter speed set at 1/2500 of a second to freeze them in flight without motion blur. I was using a 100mm-400mm zoom lens.  They only fed their young once about every 15-20 minutes despite it being 88 degrees, relatively calm, and sunny. Their feeding strategy is to bring in huge mouthfuls of tiny insects that caused their mouths to bulge on bottom (see photos). To get the photographic close-ups of the nest and nestlings, I placed an extension ladder against the chimney, climbed to the top of it, then aimed the camera with a flash and short telephoto lens down the chimney 72” to the nest. For these photos, I was using a 70mm-200mm zoom lens.  The biggest problem was that the chimney was so dark inside that I had trouble manually focusing the lens on the nest as did the camera when I switched to autofocus. In the nest photos, you can see there are 5 nestlings already crowding their tiny stick and saliva nest. Their eyes are still grown closed and their feather tracts are beginning to show. Notice in the one nest photo, that the old nest off to the side corner is starting to separate from the brick wall. In the close-ups of the twig nest, you can see the shiny, amber-colored glue, produced by the adults’ specialized saliva glands to adhere the twigs to each other and the entire nest to the bricks.

Post ice cream run while driving back home, I spotted a huge flock of Chimney Swifts over a side street. I wasn’t sure how large the flock would be until we made a quick turn onto Church Street. We eagerly found a spot to pull over and hop out. I desperately wanted to get a count not being sure if they would continue flying over town. I excitedly was throwing my hands up in the air and pointing trying to get an accurate estimate of the flock. As we stood there in awe watching them feed and circle over the church, a very sweet old man came out and asked us if we were enjoying the bats. He mentioned how he saw me throwing my hands in the air and had to come out to talk to us. He had told us that in the 25 years he had lived there, he had never seen anyone stop and watch them. So, after my one failed attempt to kindly correct him about the swifts, I didn’t want to ruin his excitement. We all watched in silence and wonder as they twisted into the chimney for the night. Truly an amazing experience!! Total is a very decent estimate, wouldn’t say there was more than 550, but definitely no less than 450.

Small, cigar shaped swift, uniformly brown with paler throat. Silent. In the field I had no idea whether this was Chimney or Vaux's. After studying online resources, I started to lean toward Chimney Swift given the long wings and the bulging inner primaries. I asked for a few opinions. Tony Leukering said, "I’d go with CHSW, due to the ss bulge and the apparent lack of a paler rump. However, I’m not all that comfortable with Chaetura." Steve Mlodinow added, "I agree with Tony, looks much like a Chimney Swift. For the points Tony makes and this bird has the lankier jizz of a CHSW rather than the stubby feel of Vaux's." I will add that three days after seeing this bird, I was in Oregon and got to study Vaux's Swift, and it quickly struck me as a much faster-flapping bird than the one I'd seen in Utah, with shorter and straighter-edged wings. For all these reasons, I am now comfortable calling this a Chimney Swift. NOTE: This record was accepted by the Utah Bird Records Committee as the second confirmed record for Utah.

Media notes: Really strange observation that I'm now kicking myself over. I recorded a bird giving "chip" calls apparently from the ground, deep in some ferns. I assumed it was a warbler, but I was intrigued by the fact that a) it was on the ground, b) the chips were highly variable in pitch, and b) it NEVER moved. I did some screech-owl and Carolina Wren playback, and the bird continued to chip but didn't budge from its spot. I elected not to go in after it and flush it, since I figured I'd already stressed it enough with the playback.  And then, when I got back to my office, it suddenly hit me what was going on. The bird was most likely a downed Chimney Swift and didn't move because it literally couldn't. That would also explain the changes in pitch and the odd curved shape to its calls (which isn't typical of any warblers that I know of). The poor bird is probably going to die now. That's what I get for trying to be respectful of its space, I guess :-(

Observation Details: Record Accepted by AZ Bird Committee.  1)	Size: the bird did not appear noticeably smaller than the swallows in the same flock, suggesting Chimney Swift (VASW would be distinctly smaller than swallows);  2)	Wing shape: a distinct “primary bulge” is evident in many photos and was commented on in the field, suggesting Chimney Swift;  3)	Relative wing length: quantitative analysis of wing length and width shows these measurements to be outside of the range observed for Vaux’s Swift, but in the expected range for Chimney (ABC report has details);  4)	Rump color: this bird’s rump was not contrastingly lighter than the back, which is the expected pattern for Chimney;  5)	Color of underparts: the light gray throat transitioned abruptly to a much darker belly, which is a more expected pattern for Chimney;  6)	Terminal bar: the bird’s uppertail coverts appear in photos to reach the base of the tail barbs, this is expected for Chimney, but in Vaux’s the uppertail coverts would fall short of the base of the barbs.   Supporting media: A series of 38 photos can be found at https://flic.kr/s/aHsmc48nL5

Observation Details: Photos to reviewed later. Appeared larger, longer  winged and less frantically flappy than Vaux’s.  ST: Seen with several BARS and a PUMA. The bird did a series of loops over the cemetery on 2 different occasions. Due to overcast it was impossible to make out subtle area of paleness (or lack thereof) in the field, though some processing of Karen's photos are indicative of CHSW. While we observed it, it immediately gave both Adam and myself the impression of CHSW over VASW due to perceived structure and the high amount of soaring/gliding it was doing and perhaps "easier" wingbeats compared to what we typically see in VASW, who seemingly have to put more work in to stay airborne. During its first appearance, it was fairly high and gave uninterrupted looks allowing for good study; the second time around it was quite low and would quickly disappear behind trees. Photos are consistent with our impressions in the field, though they cannot fully capture that.

We stood in the parking lot about 25 yards from the chimney.  There was a large number of swifts flying around the chimney by 7:30 and they slowly started going down in until one last swift went into the chimney at about 8:10 - as the numbers were large we would estimate 10 at a time going in and this was feasible because it was not a constant stream - a bunch would go in and then the rest would fly around for while before more would go in.  Every time we thought we were approaching the end, more swifts would arrive at the scene.  They have this interesting behavior of "faking you out" where you're sure they are going in, but they pull up at the last second and don't enter the chimney.  Our last counts at this location in late July were 125 and 82, so the assumption would be that this large number includes migrating birds.  We were very excited so unfortunately did not get a good photo!

Description by Emmett   After getting some great looks at the continuing male Hooded Warbler, we were standing in the parking lot of the Alpine County Sheriff’s Department when Aidan called out “swift!” I saw the bird naked eye and I had a jolt of excitement because it appeared large and long-winged and I thought it was going to be a Black Swift. I raised my binoculars and realized it was a Chaetura. I started yelling, “I think it’s a Chimney!” Luckily, Aidan Brubaker was able to get some great documentation shots of this bird over the brief minute long period of observation. Aidan’s initial impression of this bird before he saw it in bins was that it may be a WTSW.  The swift was flying maybe 30 meters off the ground and was flying north to south, it made one brief circle back before heading due south again. It was associating with a single Barn Swallow that it appeared slightly larger than. The flight style was a lot less fluttery than what I associate with a VASW and it appeared to glide with its wings bent back like a Black Swift. Plumage details were challenging to make out in the field but it appeared quite dark. Structurally it seemed to have long wings and tail.    In reviewing photos after our observation, the bird appears sooty colored and when the ventral side of the bird is evenly lit, appears to have minimal contrast between the breast and throat. No great photos of the rump were obtained but one shot seems to show less contrast than would be expected in a VASW (per S. Terrill & K. Garrett). The wings appear broad but the secondary bulge that is usually a good field mark for Chimney was only evident in some photos. The shape of the wing changes an incredible amount in each photo depending on the position it is in. The bird never vocalized.   Some of the notes that I received from Kimball Garrett:   The bird looks pretty dark and sooty in all of the photos (obviously lighting dependent, but I would have thought that this many photos of a Vaux's at different angles would at least sometimes show a much paler looking bird).  Along with overall darkness, I see little contrast between the throat and the dark underparts -- yes, the throat and chest is subtly paler, but not as pale as I'd expect on a Vaux's. The very first photo you attached also doesn't seem to show an especially pale rump area, so better for Chimney  To me Vaux's gives the impression of having the wings about mid body, with less sticking out behind that in a Chimney Swift (which, in turn, seems to have wings a bit farther forward, due mostly I presume to having a longer and more substantial tail). Your bird better matches Chimney in that regard.  I've never been especially convinced about the inner primary bulge of Chimney vs. Vaux's -- probably molt-dependent and can look very different in different flight angles and modes. But Chimney seems to have larger wings, i.e. relatively longer and broader-based compared to Vaux's; your photos look good for Chimney in this regard as well.   Kimball did add this as well, “I would be happy calling your bird a Chimney, but in the absence of vocal characters I guess I'm more in the 90% camp than the 100% camp.”   I have yet to hear back from all of the experts that I emailed these photos to but the consensus so far has varied between strongly suggestive of CHSW and “looks good” for CHSW. Based on their opinions from photos and our experience in the field I feel comfortable calling this bird as Alpine’s second Chimney Swift.

This morning I was greeted with another fledgling inside the building, hanging on a window screen.  I snapped a few quick photos, then was able to grab it and release it outdoors, and it flew away over Green Lake.   What followed was quite interesting...  The flying bird was soon joined by a couple of other swifts, and at one point there were four flying together – making swoops and circles not far away. I tried to shoot a few photos, and managed to get one that appeared to be the swift I had just released, since the picture shows that it has cobwebs trailing off its tail and wing! A couple of other photos showed birds that were obviously adults, due to the heavy feather molt in their wings. A few minutes later I watched as two of the swifts suddenly swooped down toward the building and plummeted down the chimney – separated by only about 2-3 feet!    I immediately went inside and shot a few photos up through the fireplace, and could tell that least one of the swifts that had dropped inside the chimney was the same captured/released fledgling that had cobwebs hanging from it!  Before I had been able to get set up to shoot photos, I’d heard some fluttering inside the chimney, so it’s possible that one of the birds that had dropped inside was an adult – but it may have taken off again before it could get any pictures.  Besides the fledgling that had cobwebs on it (which was clinging to the masonry), two nestlings were sitting on the nest, so it seemed unlikely that they had been ones that had just dropped inside the chimney.   Later the fledgling fluttered and moved up to where it ended up clinging onto the left side of the nest.

Observation Details: *** consensus is Chimney Swift.  One strange looking swift-type bird associating with the Tree Swallows.  Much different wing shape that were not nearly as thin as a Chimney Swift, very pale almost white throat, and a very very pale rump which was buffy or very light tan colored. There was some brownish tint to the upper back and base of wings, and there was a light color to the forewings at the alula.  Overall it seemed broader/flatter than a Chimney Swift, with wings that had a much wider chord from leading to trailing edge. The bird had a dark forehead.  I couldn’t really determine size but it appeared larger than Chimney Swifts which I see all the time.  The bird also flew with very different wing beats than a Chimney Swift; much deeper vs. the fluttering of a Chimney Swift.  The bird may have been in some stage of molt judging on the wing tips(?).  I bumped into Larry Bausher later and showed him the photos and he said that it was a very strange looking bird. I agree!  Heavily cropped photos attached and feedback/ideas about this bird are welcome.

Noted this chaetura swift flying low over my neighborhood towards the beginning of my effort but thinking the bird would be gone and on its way I didn’t think much about it, until it started circling over my neighbors’ and I’s yards. I ran inside to grab my camera to document the bird and get an idea of wing shape and when I did, I was surprised to note the noticeable bulge to the inner primaries (CHSW wing-shape). In flight the bird appeared to have long wings and slower wings beats than VASW with more gliding (see video attached). I did not note much plumage-wise except the bird was overall dark with a noticeably pale throat contrasting with the rest of the plumage. I then spent the next 10 minutes trying to get as many pics as I could and using playback to get the bird to call. After it disappeared behind my neighbor’s trees it called for a couple seconds giving the typical “wet” twittering calls I am familiar with hearing from CHSW in the front-range and in the Southeast. I also have experience with many vocalizing VASW from the PNW. The bird circle my neighborhood for close to 20 minutes before I lost it.

Observation Details: As we approached Route 1 north from Rte 62 we saw a large flock of starlings with a swift very closely associating with it. It even tried to land on utility wires when they did. It was acting like one of their flock. We observed for close to half an hour from both the east and west sides of Route 1, just to get enough pics to hopefully ID to species if it turns out to be other than CHSW. After reviewing the photos our assessment of this bird is correct. We believe it is not a CHSW but do not know what else to call it. I thin this bird warrants  review by some experts. So we will send them off to someone to look at. The behavior of this bird was bizarre for a chimney swift, it was like  at times it thought it was a starling. When the starlings took off this bird would fly in with the flock. Like photographing a swift is not hard enough right! Where the starlings went this bird followed. I felt like ti’s flight style was not much off from a starling in some ways. It soared a lot, but maybe it was hungry/tired?  The way it soared the way it was hunting nothing seemed familiar. I was afraid it would get hit by a car because it was flying so low over RT 1 and maybe it did because we lost it and could not relocate it but we did re-find the flock of starlings.  The head to me is not like a CHSW, it is chunky much more dominant/wider than CHSW. A CHSW has a sickle like wing with the front edge curving, this bird has a more straight leading edge and it is evident in almost all the photos. To me CHSW look just like “they” say a cigar with wings, this bird clearly does not look like that to me. It looks almost more swallow like and in fact acted more swallow like.

Locality: Los Angeles River -- Elysian Park / Meadow Road
Observation Details: chaetura swifts observed toward east and northeast, in good light, from bluff to west of river.  We believe that as many as five were present on one occasion; only one white-throated swift was observed over the count period, so confusion from this species was low.  Characteristics in support of chimney over Vaux's are:  1) size of one bird with respect to nearby barn swallow; 2) lack of distinct pale throat and rump in majority of photos; 3) location and time of year.  With regard to the size, the photo linked below, which was taken while the swallow chased a swift over several seconds, was analyzed, with the result that the swift wingspan is at least 0.87x times that of the barn swallow.  This favors the larger chimney species.    Followed up 8/20 by K. Garrett:  "I checked out your spot on Meadow Rd. this evening around 5:45 -- at least three Chimney Swifts were readily seen, and a couple of them even came pretty close to where I was parked a couple of times. One showed no signs of primary molt, another seem to have an old outermost primary, and one had a gap around p7 or p8 -- probably some of the same individuals you photographed.  I didn't hear any of them call, but am quite confident they were Chimneys based on overall sooty color, mostly dark rumps, limited pale on the throats, relatively long-winged look, fuller body and tail than Vaux's, and long glides with relatively little flapping."    One swift was observed to have molting primaries.  Here are comments from K. Garrett regarding that:  "I don't think flight feather molt timing is helpful with Vaux's vs. Chimney -- both molt primarily on breeding grounds but can complete flight feather molt in migration (finishing Sep-Nov).  The main difference would be that birds on the breeding grounds (i.e. Chimney, but not Vaux's, here) would show all early to middle stages of flight feather molt, whereas migrants would probably be in the latter stages of flight feather molt (or will have completed it).  The birds showing no molt at all could be HY birds (of either species).  The one bird that is missing p8 and has old, worn p9-10 would seem to be less advanced in molt than expected of a Vaux's (i.e. a bird in mid-primary molt should still be on its breeding grounds), but there's probably a lot of overlap in timing of molt and in stage of molt during migration.  One or two other birds seem to have old p10 and otherwise fresh primaries (could be either species from that stage of molt alone)."    mediocre photos by CDD:          better photos by MS:

Observation Details: Continuing bird found by Emmett et al. on 8/13 and seen again by Jim Lomax on 8/15. Finally seen at 10:35 flying over the parking lot behind Alpine County government buildings. Approached from the east made a lap overhead and disappeared to the west over town. Seen for a total of about 15 seconds with no vocalizations heard. First noticed a chaetura swift flying toward us seemingly as large as the swallows we’d been seeing all morning. In the field we noticed the long tail and streamlined body as opposed to a more short square tailed VASW. Photos support this and also show longer wings although plumage details were hard to discern. Flight was powerful and direct reminiscent of WTSW without twittering frantic flutters we’ve observed in VASW. When banking in turns the bird would glide and lock its wings as I’ve observed CHSW do elsewhere. Photos tba

Description by Emmett   After getting some great looks at the continuing male Hooded Warbler, we were standing in the parking lot of the Alpine County Sheriff’s Department when Aidan called out “swift!” I saw the bird naked eye and I had a jolt of excitement because it appeared large and long-winged and I thought it was going to be a Black Swift. I raised my binoculars and realized it was a Chaetura. I started yelling, “I think it’s a Chimney!” Luckily, Aidan Brubaker was able to get some great documentation shots of this bird over the brief minute long period of observation. Aidan’s initial impression of this bird before he saw it in bins was that it may be a WTSW.  The swift was flying maybe 30 meters off the ground and was flying north to south, it made one brief circle back before heading due south again. It was associating with a single Barn Swallow that it appeared slightly larger than. The flight style was a lot less fluttery than what I associate with a VASW and it appeared to glide with its wings bent back like a Black Swift. Plumage details were challenging to make out in the field but it appeared quite dark. Structurally it seemed to have long wings and tail.    In reviewing photos after our observation, the bird appears sooty colored and when the ventral side of the bird is evenly lit, appears to have minimal contrast between the breast and throat. No great photos of the rump were obtained but one shot seems to show less contrast than would be expected in a VASW (per S. Terrill & K. Garrett). The wings appear broad but the secondary bulge that is usually a good field mark for Chimney was only evident in some photos. The shape of the wing changes an incredible amount in each photo depending on the position it is in. The bird never vocalized.   Some of the notes that I received from Kimball Garrett:   The bird looks pretty dark and sooty in all of the photos (obviously lighting dependent, but I would have thought that this many photos of a Vaux's at different angles would at least sometimes show a much paler looking bird).  Along with overall darkness, I see little contrast between the throat and the dark underparts -- yes, the throat and chest is subtly paler, but not as pale as I'd expect on a Vaux's. The very first photo you attached also doesn't seem to show an especially pale rump area, so better for Chimney  To me Vaux's gives the impression of having the wings about mid body, with less sticking out behind that in a Chimney Swift (which, in turn, seems to have wings a bit farther forward, due mostly I presume to having a longer and more substantial tail). Your bird better matches Chimney in that regard.  I've never been especially convinced about the inner primary bulge of Chimney vs. Vaux's -- probably molt-dependent and can look very different in different flight angles and modes. But Chimney seems to have larger wings, i.e. relatively longer and broader-based compared to Vaux's; your photos look good for Chimney in this regard as well.   Kimball did add this as well, “I would be happy calling your bird a Chimney, but in the absence of vocal characters I guess I'm more in the 90% camp than the 100% camp.”   I have yet to hear back from all of the experts that I emailed these photos to but the consensus so far has varied between strongly suggestive of CHSW and “looks good” for CHSW. Based on their opinions from photos and our experience in the field I feel comfortable calling this bird as Alpine’s second Chimney Swift.

I managed to capture photos of one taking a branch. I've seen this behavior a couple of times on Theodore Roosevelt Island. The Swifts will dart in and out of the woods at a low height and then emerge with a branch they have broken off. It looked to me that some of them were "hovering", like a hummingbird, to scout out potential sticks and then come back to get them — I believe they are speeding through and using their momentum to pluck/break the small branches.

Flying around and calling right when I pulled in to the library, ducked down into a chimney of the Cascade County Human Resources building just east of the library shortly after I acquired a short but decent recording. I waited for over an hour trying to get a better recording. I was able to acquire one more poor recording before I grew tired of waiting. Very challenging to get a quality recording with all the background noise, though I heard them often and am very familiar with the call. Call very sharp, staccato chattering that is typical of this species. Lacking the high buzzy end notes that vasw gives. Habitat PERFECT! Seen well, structure good for chsw, long “cigar shaped” body with considerably longer tail proportionate to the body than vasw. Wings also very long. Display flighting, where they do the tblo-like pulling back of the wings while drifting down and calling. At least four (maximum number seen together), but very probably more throughout downtown. When I was here a few days ago I heard these and did not register that they were rare, so I came back to confirm after making a checklist and realizing my mistake. I heard them at two other spots in downtown as well on Friday.

In spite of the coastal and sea-faring birds, swifts might have made the most impressive appearance of the day. There was a large and steady flight throughout the afternoon, picking up in quantity towards sunset. CLR made concerted efforts to keep counting passing birds, but given the size of the flight, we would have been better off making multiple rate estimates. That said, this is likely a very conservative count as most of the CHSW flight was actually behind us (over the batture scrub or beyond the levee itself). I got the impression that they passed in loose "flocks" of birds, as we would often see a large dispersed mob amassing above the batture forest to our N and then leak out and stream SSW along the river edge. If a reasonable amount of time had passed, I would scan the levee and add this to the tally, which often resulted in counts of 50-100 CHSWs in a single scan.

Three fledglings were near the nest this morning, and I took several photos up into the fireplace (photos attached).  After I went outside I watched the chimney for a little while.  One bird dropped in at 6:35 am. -- probably an adult??  Begging calls could be heard for a short time, emanating from the chimney.  The bird left again at 6:38, dropping low from chimney over the roof, to the north, as I'd seen before.  It headed out over the lake, disappearing from sight.

Media notes: Fledgling hanging on a window screen.
Observation Details: I returned to the chimney this morning to check the progress of the nest, and could see only three nestlings – so I figured that one of them had fledged.  I snapped a few photos (along with a little video that shows them stretching their wings), and then left them at peace.    As I was leaving I happened to notice that there was a Chimney Swift hanging on one of the window screens inside the building. This was actually a concern that I’d had a few days ago, wondering if it could happen that a fledgling might go DOWN into the fireplace, rather than UP the flue to exit the chimney.  Well, this apparently happened...  I shot a few photos of the fledgling hanging there, and of course wondered how long it had been there, and how hungry it might be – since I hadn’t been there for three days.  It could have happened earlier this morning, or who knows, the fledgling could have been there for a day or two?!   It was at the far end of the room from the fireplace, and it seemed unlikely that the parents had come down into the room to feed it there.  I was able to gently grab it and take it outside, and tried to hang the youngster on the outside of the chimney – but unfortunately it didn’t stay there, and it immediately took flight.  I watched it as it flew away, soon flying out over Green Lake, and I worried that it might drop down into the water.  But it seemed to fly pretty well, and I watched it making big circles up in the sky over the lake, until I lost it from view behind some trees.  Hopefully it will reunite with its parents and get something to eat!  The open fireplace certainly creates a risk for this to happen again with its siblings, so I’ll try to get over there daily to check for the same thing happening again...

Record Accepted by AZ Bird Committee.  1)	Size: the bird did not appear noticeably smaller than the swallows in the same flock, suggesting Chimney Swift (VASW would be distinctly smaller than swallows);  2)	Wing shape: a distinct “primary bulge” is evident in many photos and was commented on in the field, suggesting Chimney Swift;  3)	Relative wing length: quantitative analysis of wing length and width shows these measurements to be outside of the range observed for Vaux’s Swift, but in the expected range for Chimney (ABC report has details);  4)	Rump color: this bird’s rump was not contrastingly lighter than the back, which is the expected pattern for Chimney;  5)	Color of underparts: the light gray throat transitioned abruptly to a much darker belly, which is a more expected pattern for Chimney;  6)	Terminal bar: the bird’s uppertail coverts appear in photos to reach the base of the tail barbs, this is expected for Chimney, but in Vaux’s the uppertail coverts would fall short of the base of the barbs.   Supporting media: A series of 38 photos can be found at https://flic.kr/s/aHsmc48nL5

Observation Details: As we approached Route 1 north from Rte 62 we saw a large flock of starlings with a swift very closely associating with it. It even tried to land on utility wires when they did. It was acting like one of their flock. We observed for close to half an hour from both the east and west sides of Route 1, just to get enough pics to hopefully ID to species if it turns out to be other than CHSW. After reviewing the photos our assessment of this bird is correct. We believe it is not a CHSW but do not know what else to call it. I thin this bird warrants  review by some experts. So we will send them off to someone to look at. The behavior of this bird was bizarre for a chimney swift, it was like  at times it thought it was a starling. When the starlings took off this bird would fly in with the flock. Like photographing a swift is not hard enough right! Where the starlings went this bird followed. I felt like ti’s flight style was not much off from a starling in some ways. It soared a lot, but maybe it was hungry/tired?  The way it soared the way it was hunting nothing seemed familiar. I was afraid it would get hit by a car because it was flying so low over RT 1 and maybe it did because we lost it and could not relocate it but we did re-find the flock of starlings.  The head to me is not like a CHSW, it is chunky much more dominant/wider than CHSW. A CHSW has a sickle like wing with the front edge curving, this bird has a more straight leading edge and it is evident in almost all the photos. To me CHSW look just like “they” say a cigar with wings, this bird clearly does not look like that to me. It looks almost more swallow like and in fact acted more swallow like.

Observation Details: After a nearly two hour wait I finally began seeing swallows and swifts appearing late in the day and shortly later I managed to pick out several Chaetura.  Unfortunately, these birds never really came all that close, so I was stuck scoping them from a distance and trying to get distant photos, some of which came out reasonably well.  The Chaetura that I saw appeared generally dark, long-winged, and not really all that much smaller than the White-throated Swifts, suggesting that they indeed were Chimney Swifts.  More specifically, I noted that these birds flew with fluttery wing-beats that were faster and possibly also deeper than those of the White-throated Swifts.  The were also somewhat smaller than the other swifts but about the same size as the Barn Swallows, which seems larger than I would have expected from Vaux's Swift.  The head, neck, and body were plump and shorter than those of the White-throated Swifts and the slightly paler feathers of the rump reached well out the tail, which when once seen spread was rounded.  I thought these birds had longer and slimmer wings that I would have expected from a Vaux's Swift and I noted none of the obvious wing molt that was evident in photos of these birds taken over the past two weeks or so.  Given the distance and the late-afternoon light, it was difficult for me to see much detail on the plumage of these birds, but in general, they appeared to be rather evenly dark below and even more so above.  I did think the throat was a somewhat paler shade of gray, but even the throat appeared to be medium-gray if not darker and the rest of the underparts appeared more sooty gray.  The back and wings appeared to be blackish, so even though the rump was a relatively dark shade of brownish-gray, it nevertheless contrasted as somewhat paler than the back, and when I saw the spread tail, I noted a narrow band of blackish coloration beyond the end of the rump.  My photos may show additional details that I failed to note in the field, but the superficial description above is about all I can recall from my observations in the field.

Locality: Los Angeles River -- Elysian Park / Meadow Road
Observation Details: chaetura swifts observed toward east and northeast, in good light, from bluff to west of river.  We believe that as many as five were present on one occasion; only one white-throated swift was observed over the count period, so confusion from this species was low.  Characteristics in support of chimney over Vaux's are:  1) size of one bird with respect to nearby barn swallow; 2) lack of distinct pale throat and rump in majority of photos; 3) location and time of year.  With regard to the size, the photo linked below, which was taken while the swallow chased a swift over several seconds, was analyzed, with the result that the swift wingspan is at least 0.87x times that of the barn swallow.  This favors the larger chimney species.    Followed up 8/20 by K. Garrett:  "I checked out your spot on Meadow Rd. this evening around 5:45 -- at least three Chimney Swifts were readily seen, and a couple of them even came pretty close to where I was parked a couple of times. One showed no signs of primary molt, another seem to have an old outermost primary, and one had a gap around p7 or p8 -- probably some of the same individuals you photographed.  I didn't hear any of them call, but am quite confident they were Chimneys based on overall sooty color, mostly dark rumps, limited pale on the throats, relatively long-winged look, fuller body and tail than Vaux's, and long glides with relatively little flapping."    One swift was observed to have molting primaries.  Here are comments from K. Garrett regarding that:  "I don't think flight feather molt timing is helpful with Vaux's vs. Chimney -- both molt primarily on breeding grounds but can complete flight feather molt in migration (finishing Sep-Nov).  The main difference would be that birds on the breeding grounds (i.e. Chimney, but not Vaux's, here) would show all early to middle stages of flight feather molt, whereas migrants would probably be in the latter stages of flight feather molt (or will have completed it).  The birds showing no molt at all could be HY birds (of either species).  The one bird that is missing p8 and has old, worn p9-10 would seem to be less advanced in molt than expected of a Vaux's (i.e. a bird in mid-primary molt should still be on its breeding grounds), but there's probably a lot of overlap in timing of molt and in stage of molt during migration.  One or two other birds seem to have old p10 and otherwise fresh primaries (could be either species from that stage of molt alone)."    mediocre photos by CDD:          better photos by MS:

Observation Details: ***1st Island Record As I got out of the truck I was immediately aware of a group of White-throated Swifts foraging and vocalizing overhead. I do not often see large groups of swifts continuously foraging here, so I paused to observe them. The first swift I looked at with binoculars was not a White-throated, but a Chaetura!!! The bird was dark overall, with a  paler throat and was bigger than the adjacent White-throated Swifts. Although timing and location supports Chimney over Vaux's, I figured my best bet at separating the two was to focus on getting photos. Photos show several field marks for Chimney, including the overall shape/structure, with the body appearing long behind the wings and the "bulge" in the primaries. Overall, its plumage was dark with little contrast except for the lighter colored throat. While foraging, the bird did often glide for seconds at a time, which I later learned is a habit of Chimney Swifts.

Locality: Dairy Mart Road--Tijuana River/sod farm (view from road only)
Observation Details: The Chimney Swift appeared at precisely 6:45am flying in from northwest direction from the Dairy Mart Pond area where Dave Povey had seen it flying a bit earlier. Some 5-10 minutes later Vaux's Swift began to arrive to make up a group about 10 birds in total.  I left about 8:20am and bird still present. Watched by several observers this morning.  The Chimney Swift appeared slightly larger in size than nearby Vaux's Swift with larger primary bulge after the secondaries and larger primary wing shape visible in many angles and not only when wing flexed wide open. Also more uniformly dark in coloration with small contrast in the upperparts, pale throat patch noticeable against darker belly, face rather aggressive looking with fine white line above and stopping just forward of the eye visible. Underparts quite dark and could be picked out readily from paler Vaux's especially when green willow trees in the background.  Flight style was noticeably different from the Vaux's with slightly slower flapping but more powerful looking flight generation than twittery haywire flight energy of the Vaux's.  Also, as other observers noted, the Chimney Swift taking long continuous glides in horizontal flight across the feeding area of the swifts. In addition did seem to often appear a bit higher in the sky more regularly.  Feather wear apparent and matches photos taken by yesterday's observers.

Observation Details: Record Accepted by AZ Bird Committee.  1)	Size: the bird did not appear noticeably smaller than the swallows in the same flock, suggesting Chimney Swift (VASW would be distinctly smaller than swallows);  2)	Wing shape: a distinct “primary bulge” is evident in many photos and was commented on in the field, suggesting Chimney Swift;  3)	Relative wing length: quantitative analysis of wing length and width shows these measurements to be outside of the range observed for Vaux’s Swift, but in the expected range for Chimney (ABC report has details);  4)	Rump color: this bird’s rump was not contrastingly lighter than the back, which is the expected pattern for Chimney;  5)	Color of underparts: the light gray throat transitioned abruptly to a much darker belly, which is a more expected pattern for Chimney;  6)	Terminal bar: the bird’s uppertail coverts appear in photos to reach the base of the tail barbs, this is expected for Chimney, but in Vaux’s the uppertail coverts would fall short of the base of the barbs.   Supporting media: A series of 38 photos can be found at https://flic.kr/s/aHsmc48nL5

*** consensus is Chimney Swift.  One strange looking swift-type bird associating with the Tree Swallows.  Much different wing shape that were not nearly as thin as a Chimney Swift, very pale almost white throat, and a very very pale rump which was buffy or very light tan colored. There was some brownish tint to the upper back and base of wings, and there was a light color to the forewings at the alula.  Overall it seemed broader/flatter than a Chimney Swift, with wings that had a much wider chord from leading to trailing edge. The bird had a dark forehead.  I couldn’t really determine size but it appeared larger than Chimney Swifts which I see all the time.  The bird also flew with very different wing beats than a Chimney Swift; much deeper vs. the fluttering of a Chimney Swift.  The bird may have been in some stage of molt judging on the wing tips(?).  I bumped into Larry Bausher later and showed him the photos and he said that it was a very strange looking bird. I agree!  Heavily cropped photos attached and feedback/ideas about this bird are welcome.

Observation Details: The bird first flew past Nick and I at ~5pm next to Heligoland. It seemed long winged so my first impression was WTSW - but it then doubled back in front of Shobrik and I realized it was a chaetura. We watched it for about 10 minutes, usually in view flying low over the rocky slopes in front of Shobrik and out over the water. A Merlin attacked it twice, sending it out across the water not to be seen again. In the field I noted it was very dark on the rump and underp at all angles, and had very long, back swept wings. The throat contrasted slightly with the darker belly, but was also gray rather than ashy white. The wing profile is shown well in the (unedited) photos, as is the throat and rump. The bird did not vocalize. It glided around the area, flapping only occasionally with less fluttery beats.

De tels cris doivent certainement surprendre les éventuels prédateurs qui se risqueraient à entrer dans la cabane! Nous avons circulé dans les routes forestières de ce bûcher durant plus de deux heures sans voir un seul martinet adulte!

Observation Details: Wake Audubon CHSW coordinator asked me to monitor this chimney.  Chimney is part of a one-story brick building across from Professional Court at 1520 East Millbrook Road, Raleigh, NC.  (It does not appear to be capped but I can't say for certain that is open).   Several CHSW were flying over the chimney when I arrived. Usual pattern: several Swifts, then gone, then reappear with a bigger group every five minutes or so.   But they did NOT roost inside this chimney! Estimated Counts:  4 CHSW at 18:50. 32 at 19:00. 75 at 19:05. 150 at 19:10, last seen at 19:13 and dropping to ZERO thereafter!  All the swifts flew en masse to the South at 19:13.... Actual Counts: 0 at 19:15, 19:20, 19:25, 9:30, still zero at 19:35 (too dark at that point for swifts to be flying). I had a clear view of the chimney and I am certain that they NEVER entered the chimney. Perhaps they are using it as a recruitment center to gather more swifts for a larger roost in the area. They might even be part of the massive flock that gathers downtown this time of year. The high count of 150 is a conservative estimate of the largest number, seen at 19:13 (when they disappeared).

One bird appeared to have more tapered wings but both were molting, so difficult to determine true shape.

Observation Details: Continuing bird found by Emmett et al. on 8/13 and seen again by Jim Lomax on 8/15. Finally seen at 10:35 flying over the parking lot behind Alpine County government buildings. Approached from the east made a lap overhead and disappeared to the west over town. Seen for a total of about 15 seconds with no vocalizations heard. First noticed a chaetura swift flying toward us seemingly as large as the swallows we’d been seeing all morning. In the field we noticed the long tail and streamlined body as opposed to a more short square tailed VASW. Photos support this and also show longer wings although plumage details were hard to discern. Flight was powerful and direct reminiscent of WTSW without twittering frantic flutters we’ve observed in VASW. When banking in turns the bird would glide and lock its wings as I’ve observed CHSW do elsewhere. Photos tba

Description by Emmett   After getting some great looks at the continuing male Hooded Warbler, we were standing in the parking lot of the Alpine County Sheriff’s Department when Aidan called out “swift!” I saw the bird naked eye and I had a jolt of excitement because it appeared large and long-winged and I thought it was going to be a Black Swift. I raised my binoculars and realized it was a Chaetura. I started yelling, “I think it’s a Chimney!” Luckily, Aidan Brubaker was able to get some great documentation shots of this bird over the brief minute long period of observation. Aidan’s initial impression of this bird before he saw it in bins was that it may be a WTSW.  The swift was flying maybe 30 meters off the ground and was flying north to south, it made one brief circle back before heading due south again. It was associating with a single Barn Swallow that it appeared slightly larger than. The flight style was a lot less fluttery than what I associate with a VASW and it appeared to glide with its wings bent back like a Black Swift. Plumage details were challenging to make out in the field but it appeared quite dark. Structurally it seemed to have long wings and tail.    In reviewing photos after our observation, the bird appears sooty colored and when the ventral side of the bird is evenly lit, appears to have minimal contrast between the breast and throat. No great photos of the rump were obtained but one shot seems to show less contrast than would be expected in a VASW (per S. Terrill & K. Garrett). The wings appear broad but the secondary bulge that is usually a good field mark for Chimney was only evident in some photos. The shape of the wing changes an incredible amount in each photo depending on the position it is in. The bird never vocalized.   Some of the notes that I received from Kimball Garrett:   The bird looks pretty dark and sooty in all of the photos (obviously lighting dependent, but I would have thought that this many photos of a Vaux's at different angles would at least sometimes show a much paler looking bird).  Along with overall darkness, I see little contrast between the throat and the dark underparts -- yes, the throat and chest is subtly paler, but not as pale as I'd expect on a Vaux's. The very first photo you attached also doesn't seem to show an especially pale rump area, so better for Chimney  To me Vaux's gives the impression of having the wings about mid body, with less sticking out behind that in a Chimney Swift (which, in turn, seems to have wings a bit farther forward, due mostly I presume to having a longer and more substantial tail). Your bird better matches Chimney in that regard.  I've never been especially convinced about the inner primary bulge of Chimney vs. Vaux's -- probably molt-dependent and can look very different in different flight angles and modes. But Chimney seems to have larger wings, i.e. relatively longer and broader-based compared to Vaux's; your photos look good for Chimney in this regard as well.   Kimball did add this as well, “I would be happy calling your bird a Chimney, but in the absence of vocal characters I guess I'm more in the 90% camp than the 100% camp.”   I have yet to hear back from all of the experts that I emailed these photos to but the consensus so far has varied between strongly suggestive of CHSW and “looks good” for CHSW. Based on their opinions from photos and our experience in the field I feel comfortable calling this bird as Alpine’s second Chimney Swift.

Observation Details: Continuing. Maybe 2 (but birds were swiftly moving, flying out of view, and returning, so hard to keep track of individuals).  Several Vaux's were present for comparison. Observation Details: Small, cigar shaped swift, uniformly brown with paler throat. Silent. In the field I had no idea whether this was Chimney or Vaux's. After studying online resources, I started to lean toward Chimney Swift given the long wings and the bulging inner primaries. I asked for a few opinions. Tony Leukering said, "I’d go with CHSW, due to the ss bulge and the apparent lack of a paler rump. However, I’m not all that comfortable with Chaetura." Steve Mlodinow added, "I agree with Tony, looks much like a Chimney Swift. For the points Tony makes and this bird has the lankier jizz of a CHSW rather than the stubby feel of Vaux's." I will add that three days after seeing this bird, I was in Oregon and got to study Vaux's Swift, and it quickly struck me as a much faster-flapping bird than the one I'd seen in Utah, with shorter and straighter-edged wings. For all these reasons, I am now comfortable calling this a Chimney Swift. NOTE: This record was accepted by the Utah Bird Records Committee as the second confirmed record for Utah.

Observation Details: Durant la période précédent l'entrée d'un premier adulte, les oisillons ont faient plusieurs séances de battements d'ailes. À 19 h. 44 première observation alors qu'un adulte entre en flèche. Une seconde observation a lieu moins d'une minute plus tard avec l'entrée d'un second adulte. À ce moment là les deux adultes sont dans la cheminée. Les deux adultes sortent de la cheminée respectivement après avoir passés 1 min. 44 sec. et 1 min. 46 sec. à l'intérieur. Il est 19 h. 46. Le soleil se couche à 19 h. 56. L'intervalle avant la prochaine visite d'un adulte (presque 16 minutes) est meublé de plusieurs vocalises et de quelques séances de battements d'ailes. À 20 h. 01 la cinquième observation, est un adulte entrant en flèche. La sixième observation se déroule à 20 h. 04, les deux adultes sont de nouveaux ensemble dans la cheminée. À partir de ce moment, il y aura toujours un adulte dans la cheminée. À 20 h. 07 un adulte sort et s'envole vers le bas du village. La huitième observation se déroule à 20 h. 11 avec l'entrée en vrille d'un individu. Il s'écoulera 1 min. 40 sec. avant la sortie d'un adulte. Cette sortie à 20 h. 12 sera le dernier contacte visuel avec un martinet ramoneur et la neuvième observation. Il s'écoulera 24 minutes sans que je n'observe un martinet ramoneur. Durant cette séquence, les oisillons seront particulièrement bruyants cela étant dû, à mon humble avis, par la présence constante d'un des deux adultes à la cheminée. On distingue assez facilement durant ce segment, quelques séquences où l'adulte lance ses cliquetis singuliers. Sans en être certain à 100%, le spectrogramme laisse croire à une entrée du second adulte à 20 h. 21 min. Une entrée qui m'aurait échappée durant ma surveillance lors d'un mauvais clignement des yeux!. Une fois l'excitation passée cette dernière entrée, les 10 dernières minutes furent meublées par un enchaînements de séances de quémandages. La séance de surveillance se termine à 20 h. 33.

Observation Details: Première observation à 8 h. 09 d'un individu approchant la cheminée de l'église à l'horizontale en provenance de l'édifice Rose D. Lavoie. Demeure 2 minutes et 5 secondes dans la cheminée avant d'en ressortir à 8 h. 11 minutes vers le bas du village. Durant le laps de temps menant à la troisième observation d'un adulte à la cheminée, soit 18 minutes, les oisillons vocalisent régulièrement. De plus, il est raisonnable de dire qu'ils s'exercent à battre des ailes à même la coupole de leur nid par le vrombissement de leurs coups d'ailes énergiques. Il est plus hasardeux de mentionner qu'un individu réussi à s'élever de son nid par l'écho de ses battements d'ailes s'amenuisant et s'assourdissant au gré de son élévation avant de redescendre ou de s'accrocher à la paroi interne de la cheminée. Troisième observation à 8 h. 29 minutes alors qu'un adulte entre dans la cheminée à la verticale, descendant en papillonant doucement. Demeure dans la cheminée 1 minute 28 secondes avant de sortir à 8 h. 30 en direction du bas du village. Dans la l'attente de la prochaine visite d'un adulte, il s'écoule 9 minutes qui seront beaucoup plus calme que la première période, autant vocalement que pour les exercices de battements d'ailes et "de vol". La cinquième observation se fait à 8 h. 39 alors qu'un adulte décrit une loupe au-dessus du terrain de jeux municipal avant de s'engouffrer dans la cheminée en rasant sa tête. L'adulte demeure dans la cheminée 4 min. 31 sec. avant de s'envoler vers le bas du village à 8 h. 44. Fin de la surveillance des martinets ramoneurs à cette même heure.

A “cigar with wings.” Shorter-tailed and longer-winged than a swallow, with more erratic, excited-Muppet-style flight. So definitely a swift, and while it’s a little early for a Chimney Swift, they’ve been recorded here this early before, and it seems much more likely to be a Chimney than any other kind of Swift. Size and plumage also seemed to match Chimney. But I know some have wondered whether it could be something else (just based on time of year) so I’m happy to change this ID if it turns out to be some sort of vagrant. After outside help from Advanced Bird ID Facebook group and more photos, Chaetura species was identified as Chimney (the more likely candidate when compared to Vaux's). Notes supporting CHSW from the group include: "First photo shows definite bulge to inner primaries, indicating Chimney. Those backlit shots show that the uppertail coverts extend all the way to the the base of the barbs of the tail feathers, which supports Chimney.". Personal notes at the time include: "Loosely associating with two Tree Swallows. Seemed quite small and short-winged, unfortunately did not call during the observation. Only one previous record for Chimney Swift accepted in this area and a single record for Vaux’s Swift accepted in the state further southwest (Vaux’s was reported around the same time of year back in 2004). Flight style appeared flappy during observation, but hard to judge with winds picking up as small storm started to develop.". Documentation photos.

Observation Details: In spite of the coastal and sea-faring birds, swifts might have made the most impressive appearance of the day. There was a large and steady flight throughout the afternoon, picking up in quantity towards sunset. CLR made concerted efforts to keep counting passing birds, but given the size of the flight, we would have been better off making multiple rate estimates. That said, this is likely a very conservative count as most of the CHSW flight was actually behind us (over the batture scrub or beyond the levee itself). I got the impression that they passed in loose "flocks" of birds, as we would often see a large dispersed mob amassing above the batture forest to our N and then leak out and stream SSW along the river edge. If a reasonable amount of time had passed, I would scan the levee and add this to the tally, which often resulted in counts of 50-100 CHSWs in a single scan.

Observation Details: A large swirling flock of Chaetura that extended from The Chapel to the Lod Cook Hotel, but most were over the large trees next to the South Frat Lot. We spent most of the time on this list trying to sort through these birds and look for Vaux's. Tried to count them many times, but it was hard due to it being a swirling mass of swifts and swallows, so this is a rough count. We did on a few occasions get close to what we thought was a reliable 1x1 count, and most were in the low-mid 30s. Since most of the birds were backlit against the clouds, trying to identify them was challenging, and I'm not at all confident that we got all of them correct. Most of the birds appeared, to me, to show field marks of Chimney, including long heads and tails, fairly broad angular wings especially broad at the secondaries, and flew with deep somewhat rowing wing beats. Those times that the birds would fly in front of the trees, or lower to the ground, most birds had rather dark rumps and throats. Many photos to be added soon.

Flew overhead as I was walking the creek bed; did not vocalize; Chaetura swifts molting inner primaries. Seen from below so could not determine rump color. Most likely Chimney Swifts as Vaux's has never been documented in Texas. Attached images are of two different birds. One bird appeared to have more tapered wings but both were molting, so difficult to determine true shape.

Observation Details: Two nestlings were initially near the nest (perched beside it), and another one was found alongside one of the building's walls.  I released that one outdoors, and it flew away.  One of the two nestlings fluttered up inside the chimney flue, and clung to a joint about 2 feet about the nest.  The other nestling later moved back on top of the nest.

Media notes: Fledgling hanging on a window screen.
Observation Details: I returned to the chimney this morning to check the progress of the nest, and could see only three nestlings – so I figured that one of them had fledged.  I snapped a few photos (along with a little video that shows them stretching their wings), and then left them at peace.    As I was leaving I happened to notice that there was a Chimney Swift hanging on one of the window screens inside the building. This was actually a concern that I’d had a few days ago, wondering if it could happen that a fledgling might go DOWN into the fireplace, rather than UP the flue to exit the chimney.  Well, this apparently happened...  I shot a few photos of the fledgling hanging there, and of course wondered how long it had been there, and how hungry it might be – since I hadn’t been there for three days.  It could have happened earlier this morning, or who knows, the fledgling could have been there for a day or two?!   It was at the far end of the room from the fireplace, and it seemed unlikely that the parents had come down into the room to feed it there.  I was able to gently grab it and take it outside, and tried to hang the youngster on the outside of the chimney – but unfortunately it didn’t stay there, and it immediately took flight.  I watched it as it flew away, soon flying out over Green Lake, and I worried that it might drop down into the water.  But it seemed to fly pretty well, and I watched it making big circles up in the sky over the lake, until I lost it from view behind some trees.  Hopefully it will reunite with its parents and get something to eat!  The open fireplace certainly creates a risk for this to happen again with its siblings, so I’ll try to get over there daily to check for the same thing happening again...

First seen @ 11:56AM, again mixed in with the hirundine flock, mainly over the center of the golf course. Seen again at 12:00 pm 12:05 pm, and finally at 12:08 pm. Typical chaetura profile, wings often held stiffly and slightly downward during glides glides. Lacked the twinkly wing beats of the palm-swift. Throat pale brown (buff), otherwise uniformly dark brown with a lighter brown strip down the center of breast and belly. visible in good light.  Will add photos later

Observation Details: Chimney Swift entering chimney: 2:00pm 1 entered and exited in less than a minute; 2:05pm 1 entered and exited in less than a minute; 2:45pm 1 entered and exited in less than a minute; 3:15pm 1 entered and exited a minute later; 3:45pm 1 entered and exited in less than a minute; 4:35pm 1 entered and exited 2 minutes later; 4:57pm 1 exited; 5:05pm 1 entered; 5:15pm 1 exited; 5:21pm 1 entered. Intermittent light rain most of the time. Chimney Swifts only entered chimney when rain eased up a bit or stopped. One pair seemed to favor the chimney. Not sure if carrying food, nesting material or anything into chimney. When one entered, did a different one leave to feed? Or is it the same one that entered? Also do not know where they were the one that exited went when it rained. Once the rain ceased, more were seen in the air. Six were together and very vocal around 5:00pm.

Observation Details: *Late. **High count. Initially, I was surprised to see one bird at the south end of the bogs (Halifax end of the WMA), but subsequently I discovered that at least seventeen birds were present (possibly as many as twenty).  The birds were concentrated in the habitat restoration area (i.e., the section with patches of open water and no Wool-grass) on the east side of the southern end of the bogs.  The birds were carefully counted and photographed.

Observation Details: continuing bird. Possibly more than one. Mostly with Vaux's just north of the Los Feliz bridge. Larger and longer winged than Vaux's, also appeared a bit chunkier. Distinctly darker; entirely sooty black except for a gray throat. The throat was darker than a Vaux's, though still contrasted with the rest of the darker body. Also, no pale rump region as in Vaux's. Poor photos.
